o Astronomer|pages=79\u201384|volume=11|date=January 1863|number=63|journal=[[The Atlantic|The Atlantic Monthly]]|location=[[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]|publisher=Ticknor & Fields|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]|accessdate=2019-03-21}}\n* {{cite book|last=Crew|first=Harvey W., Webb, William Bensing, Wooldridge, John |year=1892 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5Q81AAAAIAAJ&&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=Centennial History of the City of Washington, D.C. |publisher=United Brethren Publishing House |place=Dayton, Ohio |title=IV. \"Permanent Capital Site Selected\"|page=87|lccn=06028029|oclc=2843595 |accessdate=2009-05-07|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n*{{cite book|last=Graham|first=Shirley|author-link=Shirley Graham Du Bois|year=1949|url=https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/n8/mode/1up|title=Your Most Humble Servant|lccn=49011346|oclc=1036934508|accessdate=April 15, 2020|location=New York|publisher=[[Julian Messner|Julian Messner, Inc.]]|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jusserand|first=Jean Jules|author-link=Jean Jules Jusserand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2MUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=With Americans of Past and Present Days||oclc=1075914 |title=Major L'Enfant and the Federal City |location=New York |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons]] |pages=137\u2013195 |year=1916 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Latrobe|first=John H. B., Esq.|url=https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog/page/n7/mode/1up|title=Memoir of Benjamin Banneker: Read before the Maryland Historical Society at the Monthly Meeting, May 1, 1845|location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed by John D. Toy|year=1845|lccn=rc01003345|oclc=85791076|accessdate=February 29, 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Hugh Alexander|url=https://archive.org/details/preliminarycheck00morr|title=Preliminary Check List of American Almanacs: 1639-1800|work=Library of Congress|year=1907|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|oclc=577096527|lccn=06035021|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=December 31, 2018|via=[[Internet Archive]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231033020/https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0|archive-date=December 31, 2018}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/mode/1up|title=A plan of a Peace-Office for the United States|work=Essays, Literary, Moral and Philosophical.|last=Rush|first=Benjamin, M.D.|author-link=Benjamin Rush|year=1798|place=Philadelphia |publisher=Thomas and William Bradford |accessdate=2019-06-13|oclc=53177918|isbn=0912756225|lccn=88080672|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Stewart |first=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Early Maps and Surveyors of the City of Washington, D.C. |year=1899 |journal=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]] |location=Washington, D.C. |volume=2 |pages=48\u201371 |issn=0897-9049 |oclc=40326234 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2 |title=Standard History of the City of Washington From a Study of the Original Sources |last=Tindall |first=William |location=Knoxville, Tennessee |publisher=H. W. Crew and Company |year=1914 |lccn=14013663|oclc=7059152 |accessdate=2013-01-31 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso/page/n4/mode/1up|title=A sketch of the life of Benjamin Banneker: from notes taken in 1836: read by J. Saurin Norris, before the Maryland Historical Society, October 5th, 1854 |first=Martha Ellicott |last=Tyson |location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed for the Maryland Historical Society by John D. Toy |lccn=rc01003357|oclc=85794847|accessdate=2015-04-24|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first=Carter Goodwin|last=Woodson|author-link=Carter G. Woodson|year=1919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Education of the Negro Prior to 1861: A History of the Education of the Colored People of the United States from the Beginning of Slavery to the Civil War|edition=Second|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Associated Publishers, Inc.|lccn=68029024|oclc=1003200476|accessdate=April 15, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|History|United States|Maryland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banneker, Mythology and legacy of Benjamin}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Misconceptions]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Legacies by person]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlan of the City of Washington:editorial change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythology_of_Benjamin_Banneker"}
{"title_page": "David Day (Canadian writer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{About|Canadian author|the Australian historian and author|David Day (historian)|other people of the same name|David Day (disambiguation){{!}}David Day}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2017}}\n'''David Day''' (born 14 October 1947 in [[Victoria, British Columbia]]) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[author]] of more than forty books: poetry, natural history, ecology, mythology, fantasy, and children's literature. Internationally, he is best known for his literary criticism on [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and his works.<ref name=\"ABC Book World\">[http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=489 Biography at ABC Book World]</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAfter finishing high school in [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Day worked as a logger for five years on [[Vancouver Island]] before graduating from the [[University of Victoria]].  Subsequently, he has travelled widely, most frequently to [[Greece]] and Britain.\n\nDay has published six books of poems for adults and ten illustrated children's books of fiction and poetry. His non-fiction books on natural history include ''The Doomsday Book of Animals'' (1981), ''Noah's Choice: True Stories of Extinction and Survival'' (1990), and ''Nevermore: A Book of Hours \u2013 Meditations on Extinction'' (2012). His ''Doomsday Book'' became the basis for the 100-part animated-short TV series ''[[Lost Animals of the 20th Century]]'' in 1995/1996. His books on environmental activism include ''The Whale War'' (1987) and ''Eco Wars: A Layman's Guide to the Ecology Movement'' (1989).<ref name=\"Works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.daviddaybooks.com/Books%20and%20Audio.htm |title=Works |access-date=2010-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402215451/http://www.daviddaybooks.com/Books%20and%20Audio.htm |archive-date=2010-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDay's best-selling books on the life and work of Tolkien, are: ''A Tolkien Bestiary'' (1978), ''The Tolkien Companion'' (1993), ''[[Tolkien's Ring]]'' (1994), ''The Hobbit Companion'' (2000), ''Tolkien: The Illustrated Encyclopedia'' (1992) and ''The World of Tolkien'' (2003). Day's ''Tolkien's Ring'' was illustrated by Academy Award-winning artist [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]], as was ''Castles'' (1984), ''The Animals Within'' (1984), ''Gothic'' (1986) and ''Quest For King Arthur'' (1996).\n\nIn 2015 he published ''Alice\u2019s Adventures in Wonderland Decoded'' on the 150th anniversary of the publication of the [[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland|classic book]] by [[Lewis Carroll]].<ref>Random House, [http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237881/alices-adventures-in-wonderland-decoded-by-david-day/ Pre-press news release]</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''The Cowichan'' (1975)\n* ''Many Voices: An Anthology of Contemporary Canadian Indian Poetry'' (co-editor) (1977) {{ISBN|0-88894-134-X}}\n* ''The Scarlet Coat Serial'' (1981) {{ISBN|0-88878-135-0}}\n* ''The Animals Within'' (1984) {{ISBN|0-88878-135-0}}\n* ''Gothic (novel)|Gothic'' (1986) {{ISBN|978-0-920428-05-4}}\n* ''The Visions and Revelations of St. Louis the Metis'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-895449-64-2}}\n* ''Just Say 'No' to Family Values'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-55096-162-4}}\n\n=== Natural history and ecology ===\n* ''The Doomsday Book of Animals'' (1981) {{ISBN|0-670-27987-0}}\n* ''The Whale War'' (1987) {{ISBN|0-87156-775-X}}\n* ''The Eco Wars: A Layman's Guide to the Environmental Movement'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-245-54723-1}}\n* ''The Encyclopedia of Vanished Species'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-947889-30-2}}\n* ''Noah's Choice'' (1990){{ISBN|0-670-80669-2}}\n* ''True Tales of Environmental Madness'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-7207-1974-7}}\n* ''Green Penguin Book Guide'' (1992)\n* ''The Complete Rhinoceros'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-9516342-6-7}}\n* ''Nevermore: A Book of Hours \u2013 Meditations on Extinction'' (2012) {{ISBN|978-1-926802-68-8}}\n\n=== Fantasy and mythology ===\n* ''The Burroughs Bestiary'' (1978) {{ISBN|0-450-03442-9}}\n* ''A Tolkien Bestiary'' (1978, {{ISBN|0-345-28283-3}}); reprinted as ''Guide to Tolkien's World'' (2002, 1571458786) and ''Guide to Tolkien's World: A Bestiary'' (2012, 978-0753720806)\n* ''Castles'', illustrated by [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]] (1984) {{ISBN|0-07-037280-2}}\n* ''Tolkien: The Illustrated Encyclopedia'' (1992) {{ISBN|0-02-533431-X}}\n* ''The Tolkien Companion'' (1993, {{ISBN|0749315946}}); reprinted as ''A to Z of Tolkien'' (1996, 1851529217) and ''A Guide to Tolkien'' (2002, 0753705621) \n* ''[[Tolkien's Ring]]'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-261-10298-2}}\n* ''The Quest for King Arthur'' (1996) {{ISBN|0-8160-3370-6}}\n* ''The Hobbit Companion'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-57036-391-9}}\n* ''Tolkien's World'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-517-22317-1}}\n* ''The Battles of Tolkien'' (2016)\n* ''The Heroes of Tolkien'' (2017) {{ISBN|978-0-7537-3247-2}}\n* ''The Dark Powers of Tolkien'' (2018) {{ISBN|978-0-7537-3307-3}}\n* ''A Dictionary of Tolkien'' (1993) {{ISBN|978-0-75372-827-7}}\n\n=== History ===\n* ''History and Literature: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1975)\n* ''Myth and the Mountains: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1976)\n* ''Men of the Forest: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1977)\n* ''Alice\u2019s Adventures in Wonderland Decoded'' (2015)\n\n=== Children's fiction and poetry ===\n* ''The Emperor's Panda'' (1986) {{ISBN|0-396-09036-2}}\n* ''The Swan Children'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-8249-8461-7}}\n* ''The Sleeper'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-8249-8456-0}}\n* ''Aska's Animals'' (1991) {{ISBN|0-385-25315-X}}\n* ''The Big Lie'' (1991) aka ''The Walking Catfish'' {{ISBN|0-02-726360-6}}\n* ''Aska's Birds'' (1992) {{ISBN|0-385-25388-5}}\n* ''The King of the Woods'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-02-726361-4}}\n* ''Tippu'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-8120-6498-4}}\n* ''Aska's Sea Creatures'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-385-32107-4}}\n\n=== Television, radio, film and theatre ===\n* ''[[The Scarlet Coat]]'' \u2013 University of Saskatchewan Theatre (1984)\n* ''The Lost'' \u2013 CBC Radio (1984)\n* ''Gothic'' \u2013 Royal Victoria Museum Theatre (1988)\n* ''The Emperor's Panda'' \u2013 Young People's Theatre of Toronto (1988)\n* ''Noah's Choice'' \u2013 Channel 4 Television (1990)\n* ''[[Still Life at the Penguin Cafe]]'' \u2013 Ballet \u2013 BBC Television (1993)\n* ''The Whale War'' \u2013 ITV Television Documentary (1993)\n* ''[[Lost Animals of the 20th Century]]'' \u2013 Channel 4 and NHK Japan TV series (1995/1996)\n* ''Just Say 'No' to Family Values'' \u2013 Poetry and Jazz \u2013 The Senator, Toronto (1998)\n* ''[[Arthur I]]'' & ''[[Arthur II]]'' \u2013 Royal Birmingham Ballet \u2013 Covent Garden, London (2000)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://abcbookworld.com/scripter/scripter-5742/ \"DAY, David\"], biography incorporating 2012 interview, at ABCbookworld.com (BC BookWorld Archive, British Columbia)\n* {{isfdb name|21420}}\n* {{LCAuth|n77007935|David Day|34|ue}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Day, David}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Victoria, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Tolkien studies]]\n[[Category:20th-century biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian literary critics]]\n[[Category:University of Victoria alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{About|Canadian author|the Australian historian and author|David Day (historian)|other people of the same name|David Day (disambiguation){{!}}David Day}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2017}}\n'''David Day''' (born 14 October 1947 in [[Victoria, British Columbia]]) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[author]] of more than forty books: poetry, natural history, ecology, mythology, fantasy, and children's literature. Internationally, he is best known for his literary criticism on [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and his works.<ref name=\"ABC Book World\">[http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=489 Biography at ABC Book World]</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAfter finishing high school in [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Day worked as a logger for five years on [[Vancouver Island]] before graduating from the [[University of Victoria]].  Subsequently, he has travelled widely, most frequently to [[Greece]] and Britain.\n\nDay has published six books of poems for adults and ten illustrated children's books of fiction and poetry. His non-fiction books on natural history include ''The Doomsday Book of Animals'' (1981), ''Noah's Choice: True Stories of Extinction and Survival'' (1990), and ''Nevermore: A Book of Hours \u2013 Meditations on Extinction'' (2012). His ''Doomsday Book'' became the basis for the 100-part animated-short TV series ''[[Lost Animals of the 20th Century]]'' in 1995/1996. His books on environmental activism include ''The Whale War'' (1987) and ''Eco Wars: A Layman's Guide to the Ecology Movement'' (1989).<ref name=\"Works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.daviddaybooks.com/Books%20and%20Audio.htm |title=Works |access-date=2010-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402215451/http://www.daviddaybooks.com/Books%20and%20Audio.htm |archive-date=2010-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDay's best-selling books on the life and work of Tolkien, are: ''A Tolkien Bestiary'' (1978), ''The Tolkien Companion'' (1993), ''[[Tolkien's Ring]]'' (1994), ''The Hobbit Companion'' (2000), ''Tolkien: The Illustrated Encyclopedia'' (1992) and ''The World of Tolkien'' (2003). Day's ''Tolkien's Ring'' was illustrated by Academy Award-winning artist [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]], as was ''Castles'' (1984), ''The Animals Within'' (1984), ''Gothic'' (1986) and ''Quest For King Arthur'' (1996).\n\nIn 2015 he published ''Alice\u2019s Adventures in Wonderland Decoded'' on the 150th anniversary of the publication of the [[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland|classic book]] by [[Lewis Carroll]].<ref>Random House, [http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237881/alices-adventures-in-wonderland-decoded-by-david-day/ Pre-press news release]</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''The Cowichan'' (1975)\n* ''Many Voices: An Anthology of Contemporary Canadian Indian Poetry'' (co-editor) (1977) {{ISBN|0-88894-134-X}}\n* ''The Scarlet Coat Serial'' (1981) {{ISBN|0-88878-135-0}}\n* ''The Animals Within'' (1984) {{ISBN|0-88878-135-0}}\n* ''Gothic (novel)|Gothic'' (1986) {{ISBN|978-0-920428-05-4}}\n* ''The Visions and Revelations of St. Louis the Metis'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-895449-64-2}}\n* ''Just Say 'No' to Family Values'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-55096-162-4}}\n\n=== Natural history and ecology ===\n* ''The Doomsday Book of Animals'' (1981) {{ISBN|0-670-27987-0}}\n* ''The Whale War'' (1987) {{ISBN|0-87156-775-X}}\n* ''The Eco Wars: A Layman's Guide to the Environmental Movement'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-245-54723-1}}\n* ''The Encyclopedia of Vanished Species'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-947889-30-2}}\n* ''Noah's Choice'' (1990){{ISBN|0-670-80669-2}}\n* ''True Tales of Environmental Madness'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-7207-1974-7}}\n* ''Green Penguin Book Guide'' (1992)\n* ''The Complete Rhinoceros'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-9516342-6-7}}\n* ''Nevermore: A Book of Hours \u2013 Meditations on Extinction'' (2012) {{ISBN|978-1-926802-68-8}}\n\n=== Fantasy and mythology ===\n* ''The Burroughs Bestiary'' (1978) {{ISBN|0-450-03442-9}}\n* ''A Tolkien Bestiary'' (1978, {{ISBN|0-345-28283-3}}); reprinted as ''Guide to Tolkien's World'' (2002, 1571458786) and ''Guide to Tolkien's World: A Bestiary'' (2012, 978-0753720806)\n* ''Castles'', illustrated by [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]] (1984) {{ISBN|0-07-037280-2}}\n* ''Tolkien: The Illustrated Encyclopedia'' (1992) {{ISBN|0-02-533431-X}}\n* ''The Tolkien Companion'' (1993, {{ISBN|0749315946}}); reprinted as ''A to Z of Tolkien'' (1996, 1851529217) and ''A Guide to Tolkien'' (2002, 0753705621) \n* ''[[Tolkien's Ring]]'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-261-10298-2}}\n* ''The Quest for King Arthur'' (1996) {{ISBN|0-8160-3370-6}}\n* ''The Hobbit Companion'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-57036-391-9}}\n* ''Tolkien's World'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-517-22317-1}}\n* ''The Battles of Tolkien'' (2016)\n* ''The Heroes of Tolkien'' (2017) {{ISBN|978-0-7537-3247-2}}\n* ''The Dark Powers of Tolkien'' (2018) {{ISBN|978-0-7537-3307-3}}\n* ''A Dictionary of Tolkien'' (1993) {{ISBN|978-0-75372-827-7}}\n\n=== History ===\n* ''History and Literature: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1975)\n* ''Myth and the Mountains: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1976)\n* ''Men of the Forest: Sound Heritage Anthology Series'' (editor) (1977)\n* ''Alice\u2019s Adventures in Wonderland Decoded'' (2015)\n\n=== Children's fiction and poetry ===\n* ''The Emperor's Panda'' (1986) {{ISBN|0-396-09036-2}}\n* ''The Swan Children'' (1989) {{ISBN|0-8249-8461-7}}\n* ''The Sleeper'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-8249-8456-0}}\n* ''Aska's Animals'' (1991) {{ISBN|0-385-25315-X}}\n* ''The Big Lie'' (1991) aka ''The Walking Catfish'' {{ISBN|0-02-726360-6}}\n* ''Aska's Birds'' (1992) {{ISBN|0-385-25388-5}}\n* ''The King of the Woods'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-02-726361-4}}\n* ''Tippu'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-8120-6498-4}}\n* ''Aska's Sea Creatures'' (1994) {{ISBN|0-385-32107-4}}\n\n=== Television, radio, film and theatre ===\n* ''[[The Scarlet Coat]]'' \u2013 University of Saskatchewan Theatre (1984)\n* ''The Lost'' \u2013 CBC Radio (1984)\n* ''Gothic'' \u2013 Royal Victoria Museum Theatre (1988)\n* ''The Emperor's Panda'' \u2013 Young People's Theatre of Toronto (1988)\n* ''Noah's Choice'' \u2013 Channel 4 Television (1990)\n* ''[[Still Life at the Penguin Cafe]]'' \u2013 Ballet \u2013 BBC Television (1993)\n* ''The Whale War'' \u2013 ITV Television Documentary (1993)\n* ''[[Lost Animals of the 20th Century]]'' \u2013 Channel 4 and NHK Japan TV series (1995/1996)\n* ''Just Say 'No' to Family Values'' \u2013 Poetry and Jazz \u2013 The Senator, Toronto (1998)\n* ''[[Arthur I]]'' & ''[[Arthur II]]'' \u2013 Royal Birmingham Ballet \u2013 Covent Garden, London (2000)\n\n== Criticism ==\nDay's works on Tolkien, specifically his [[Compendium|compendium books]], have received criticism from both fans and experts. Criticisms range from publishing multiple books with the same text or information, misleadingly labelling his books as compendia and guides to the [[Tolkien's legendarium|Legendarium]] when they often feature Day's own interpretations and inventions (including inaccurate maps), and the outright spreading of misinformation about Legendarium lore and canon to uninformed readers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/lotr/comments/1khgtf/on_the_subject_of_maps_good_and_bad/|title=r/lotr - On the Subject of Maps (Good and Bad)|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eXhqnPDTZoU|title=We Need to Talk About David Day!|author=Talking Tolkien|date=2020-02-21|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Tolkien scholars generally discourage reading Day's books as a study of Tolkien and his works,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parmakenta.com/2013/02/tolkien-transactions-xxxiii.html|title=Tolkien Transactions XXXIII|last=Troels|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.earthlink.net/~dbratman/tolkien_bib.html|title=Biographies of C.S. Lewis|last=Bratman|first=David|website=home.earthlink.net|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> with Tolkien scholar Michael Martinez stating: \"''In Tolkien scholarship the worst insult one could deliver at any point for many years was equivalent to <nowiki>'That sounds like something David Day wrote;''</nowiki>''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.tolkien-studies.com/2007/03/07/why-wikipedia-content-cannot-be-trusted/|title=Why Wikipedia Content Cannot Be Trusted|date=2007-03-07|website=Tolkien Studies Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> and Tolkien author Steuard Jensen explaining: \"''It is important to be aware that a considerable number of other details in those vivid descriptions were invented by Day himself with little or no justification in the texts, and that these extrapolations are not distinguished from the justified facts in any way.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tolkien.slimy.com/essays/DayBooks.html|title=Notes on David Day's Tolkien Books|website=tolkien.slimy.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> [[The Tolkien Society]] does not recommend any of Day's books in their suggested readings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tolkiensociety.org/author/books-about-tolkien/|title=Books about Tolkien|date=2016-10-28|website=The Tolkien Society|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://abcbookworld.com/scripter/scripter-5742/ \"DAY, David\"], biography incorporating 2012 interview, at ABCbookworld.com (BC BookWorld Archive, British Columbia)\n* {{isfdb name|21420}}\n* {{LCAuth|n77007935|David Day|34|ue}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Day, David}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Victoria, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Tolkien studies]]\n[[Category:20th-century biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian literary critics]]\n[[Category:University of Victoria alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:b675:5800:e521:7e8d:469b:9d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Deleted libellous and false information about this author.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Day_(Canadian_writer)"}
{"title_page": "Fluid and crystallized intelligence", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=August 2019}}\n{{Confusing|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{short description|Factors of general intelligence}}\nAccording to the theory published in 1963 by the psychologist [[Raymond Cattell]],<ref name = \"Cattell & Horn\">Cattell, R. B. (1963). Theory of fluid and crystallized intelligence: A critical experiment. ''Journal of Educational Psychology, 54'', 1-22. doi:org/10.1037/h0046743</ref><ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VG85AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 Handbook of Human Intelligence]. CUP, 1982, p. 75.</ref><ref>Cattell, R. B. (1971). ''Abilities: Their structure, growth, and action''. New York: Houghton Mifflin. {{ISBN|0-395-04275-5}}.</ref> [[g factor (psychometrics)|general intelligence]] (''g'') is subdivided into '''fluid intelligence (''g''<sub>f</sub>)''' and '''crystallized intelligence (''g''<sub>c</sub>)'''. Fluid intelligence is the ability to  solve novel reasoning problems and is correlated with a number of important skills such as comprehension, problem solving, and learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Unsworth|first=Nash|last2=Fukuda|first2=Keisuke|last3=Awh|first3=Edward|last4=Vogel|first4=Edward K.|date=2014|title=Working memory and fluid intelligence: Capacity, attention control, and secondary memory retrieval|journal=Cognitive Psychology|language=en|volume=71|pages=1\u201326|doi=10.1016/j.cogpsych.2014.01.003|pmc=4484859|pmid=24531497}}</ref> Crystallized intelligence on the other hand is the ability to [[Deductive reasoning|deduce]] secondary relational abstractions by applying primary relational abstractions to each other.<ref name=\"Pseudointelligence\">Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action]. Elsevier, 1987, p. 294.</ref> However, the deduced relations among relations must be checked by fluid intelligence.<ref name=Cattell-1987-p294>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action]. Elsevier, 1987, p. 294.</ref>\n\nFluid intelligence depends on [[working memory]] capacity,<ref name=gfasWorkingMemory/> localized in the [[prefrontal cortex]].<ref name=FrontalityofWorkingMemory>Dehn, Milton J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j5ha-QRBHw8C&pg=PA69 Long-Term Memory Problems in Children and Adolescents] John Wiley & Sons, 2010, p. 69</ref> This region degenerates faster than other cortical regions in the course of aging and [[Encephalopathy|encephalopathies]].<ref name=Fuster>Fuster, Joaquin. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zuZlvNICdhUC&pg=PA44 The Prefrontal Cortex] Elsevier, 2008, p. 44</ref> Fluid intelligence peaks at around age 20, and then gradually declines.<ref>Cacioppo, John T.; Freberg, Laura. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=md8KAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT448 Discovering Psychology: The Science of Mind]. Cengage Learning, 2012, p. 448</ref>\n\n==History==\nFluid and crystallized intelligence were originally identified by [[Raymond Cattell]].<ref name = \"Cattell & Horn\"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Cattell |first=R. B. |year=1971 |title=Abilities: Their structure, growth, and action |location=New York |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |isbn=978-0-395-04275-5}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Concepts of fluid and crystallized intelligence were further developed by Cattell's student, [[John L. Horn]].\n\nSome researchers have linked the theory of fluid and crystallized abilities to [[Piaget's theory of cognitive development]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2190/AG.2.1.b |title=Piagetian Theory and the Aging Process: Extensions and Speculations |year=1971 |last1=Papalia |first1=D. |last2=Fitzgerald |first2=J. |last3=Hooper |first3=F. H. |journal=The International Journal of Aging and Human Development |volume=2 |pages=3\u201320}}</ref><ref>Schonfeld, I.S. (1986). The Genevan and Cattell-Horn conceptions of intelligence compared: The early implementation of numerical solution aids. ''Developmental Psychology, 22'', 204-212. [https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1278&context=gc_pubs]</ref> Fluid ability and Piaget's operative intelligence both concern logical thinking and the eduction of relations. Crystallized ability and Piaget's treatment of everyday learning reflect the impress of experience. Like fluid ability's relation to crystallized intelligence, Piaget's operativity is considered to be prior to, and ultimately provides the foundation for, everyday learning.\n\n==Fluid versus crystallized==\n*Fluid intelligence is [[Inductive reasoning|inductive]]<ref name=Insight2>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, p. 294</ref><ref name=Cattell-1987-p542>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA542 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, p. 542</ref> ([[Visuospatial function|visuospatial]]<ref name=Rogers>Rogers, Barrie. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JX8QAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Spatial+ability+(k)+was+shown+to+be+closely+related+to+fluid+intelligence+(gf).%22 Human Personality: Towards a Unified Theory] Vantage Press, 1972, p. 96</ref><ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rqpCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA39&dq=%22Tasks+with+a+heavy+spatial+component+are+correlated+with+measures+of+fluid+intelligence,+sometimes+almost+perfectly%22 The Nature of Human Intelligence] CUP, 2018, p. 39</ref>) intelligence,<ref name=Kassin>Kassin, Saul M. [https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Shown+on+the+right+are+the+results+of+four+measures:+two+involving+fluid+intelligence+(spatial+ability+and+inductive+reasoning)+and+two+involving+crystallized+intelligence+(verbal+ability+and+numeric+ability)%22&num=10 Psychology] Prentice Hall, 1998, p. 424</ref> which is [[Synergy|synergetic]], because its conclusions do not mechanically follow from their premises.\n*Crystallized intelligence is [[Deductive reasoning|deductive]]<ref name=Insight2/><ref name=Cattell-1987-p542/> (verbal<ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jnEYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Verbal+ability+is+also+an+excellent+measure+of+crystallized+intelligence%22 Encyclopedia of Human Intelligence] Vol. 1, Macmillan, 1995, p. 1107</ref> and numeric) intelligence,<ref name=Kassin/> which is [[Synergy|asynergetic]], because its conclusions mechanically follow from their premises.\n\nPsychologist [[Geoffrey Miller (psychologist)|Geoffrey Miller]] has argued that human intelligence and capacities for the [[cultural universal]]s of [[language]], [[music]], and [[art]] are unnecessarily sophisticated for the [[Survival of the fittest|survival]] needs of [[hunter-gatherer]]s and has argued instead that the evolution of general intelligence occurred by sexual selection rather than [[natural selection]],<ref name=\"Miller 2000\">{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Geoffrey F.|author-link=Geoffrey Miller (psychologist)|title=The Mating Mind: How Sexual Choice Shaped the Evolution of Human Nature|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|year=2000|edition=1st|isbn=978-0385495165|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/matingmind00geof}}</ref> while philosopher [[Denis Dutton]] also argued that the [[Evolutionary aesthetics|human capacity for aesthetics]] evolved by sexual selection.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dutton|first=Denis|author-link=Denis Dutton|title=The Art Instinct: Beauty, Pleasure, and Human Evolution|year=2009|pages=135\u2013163|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury Press]]|isbn=978-1596914018}}</ref> In 2007, behavioral scientist [[Daniel Nettle]] did statistical analysis relating [[Empathizing\u2013systemizing theory|empathizing\u2013systemizing theory]] as proposed by clinical psychologist [[Simon Baron-Cohen]] to the [[Big Five personality traits]] and found that the empathizing quotient had a 0.75 correlation with the [[Agreeableness|agreeability factor]] (with equivalent values on between-sex measurements), while finding that the systemizing quotient held only a 0.37 correlation to [[openness to experience]] and a 0.30 correlation with [[conscientiousness]].<ref>{{cite article|last=Nettle|first=Daniel|title=Empathizing and systemizing: What are they, and what do they contribute to our understanding of psychological sex differences?|journal=[[British Journal of Psychology]]|year=2007|volume=98|pages=237\u2013255|pmid=17456271|doi=10.1348/000712606X117612}}</ref> Nettle cites research by occupational psychologist [[Adrian Furnham]] that showed openness to experience to be positively related to general intelligence and that openness to experience is most consistently related to [[Verbal reasoning|verbal intelligence]],<ref>{{cite article|last1=Moutafi|first1=Joanna|last2=Furnham|first2=Adrian|author-link2=Adrian Furnham|last3=Crump|first3=John|title=Demographic and Personality Predictors of Intelligence: A Study Using the Neo Personality Inventory and the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator|journal=[[European Journal of Personality]]|publisher=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]]|year=2003|volume=17|issue=1|pages=79\u201394|doi=10.1002/per.471}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|last1=Moutafi|first1=Joanna|last2=Furnham|first2=Adrian|author-link2=Adrian Furnham|last3=Paltiel|first3=Laurence|title=Can Personality Factors Predict Intelligence?|journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=2005|volume=38|issue=5|pages=1021\u20131033|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2004.06.023}}</ref> and concluded that the systemizing quotient was capturing some aspect of intelligence rather than personality. that  In 2007, a [[meta-analysis]] of research on correlations between general intelligence and the Big Five showed openness to experience to have the highest correlation (0.22).<ref>{{cite book|last1=von Stumm|first1=Sophie|last2=Chamorro-Premuzic|first2=Tomas|last3=Ackerman|first3=Phillip L.|year=2011|chapter=Re-visiting intelligence-personality associations: Vindicating intellectual investment|editor-first1=Tomas|editor-last1=Chamorro-Premuzic|editor-first2=Sophie|editor-last2=von Stumm|editor-first3=Adrian|editor-last3=Furnham|title=Handbook of Individual Differences|place=[[Chichester]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]|publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]]|isbn=978-1119050308}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Judge|first1=T. A.|last2=Jackson|first2=C. L.|last3=Shaw|first3=J. C.|last4=Scott|first4=B. A.|last5=Rich|first5=B. L.|year=2007|title=Self-efficacy and work-related performance: The integral role of individual differences|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0c0fb061ac17f23520773efc68b539ab35e9a358|journal=[[Journal of Applied Psychology]]|volume=92|issue=1|pages=107\u2013127|doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.1.107|pmid=17227155}}</ref> Psychologists Akio Wakabayashi and Hiromi Kawashima, using the [[HEXACO model of personality structure]], replicated Nettle's openness to experience correlation (0.44) but found the empathizing quotient more strongly correlated to the [[Extraversion and introversion|extraversion factor]] (0.32) than the agreeability factor (0.17).<ref>{{cite article|last1=Wakabayashi|first1=Akio|last2=Kawashima|first2=Hiromi|title=Is empathizing in the E\u2013S theory similar to agreeableness? The relationship between the EQ and SQ and major personality domains|journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=2015|volume=76|pages=88\u201393|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S019188691400662X}}</ref>\n\nEach type of crystallized intelligence is independent of the other (increasing a student's proficiency in Latin does not increase the student's proficiency in algebra), but to a high degree dependent on the individual's fluid intelligence (students proficient in Latin tend to be proficient in algebra, too, because people with a high ''g''<sub>f</sub> tend to acquire more ''g''<sub>c</sub>-knowledge and at faster rates), and, to a lesser degree, on the quality of the learning environment (''e.g.'', the quality of available books).<ref>Cattell, R. B. [https://archive.org/details/intelligenceitss00catt/page/138 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, pp. 138\u201339</ref>\n\n==Factor structure==\n\nFluid intelligence generally correlates with measures of abstract reasoning and puzzle solving. Crystallized intelligence correlates with abilities that depend on knowledge and experience, such as vocabulary, general information, and analogies. Paul Kline identified a number of factors that shared a correlation of at least r=.60 with ''g''<sub>f</sub> and ''g''<sub>c</sub>.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kline |first1=P. |year=1998 |title=The new psychometrics: Science, psychology and measurement |location=London |publisher=Routledge}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Factors with {{clarify span|median loadings|date=February 2013}} of greater than 0.6 on ''g''<sub>f</sub> included induction, visualization, quantitative reasoning, and ideational fluency. Factors with median loadings of greater than 0.6 on ''g''<sub>c</sub> included verbal ability, language development, reading comprehension, sequential reasoning, and general information. It may be suggested that tests of intelligence may not be able to truly reflect levels of fluid intelligence. Some authors have suggested that unless an individual was truly interested in the problem presented, the cognitive work required may not be performed because of a lack of interest.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=1175249 |doi=10.3102/0013189X018002005 |title=Meaning and Values in Test Validation: The Science and Ethics of Assessment |year=1989 |last1=Messick |first1=Samuel |journal=Educational Researcher |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=5\u201311}}</ref> These authors contend that a low score on tests which are intended to measure fluid intelligence may reflect more a lack of interest in the tasks themselves rather than any sort of inability to complete the tasks successfully.\n\n==Measurement of fluid intelligence==\nThere are various measures that assess fluid intelligence. The [[Cattell Culture Fair III|Cattell Culture Fair IQ test]], the [[Raven's Progressive Matrices|Raven Progressive Matrices]] (RPM), and the performance subscale of the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale|WAIS]] are measures of Gf. The RPM<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raven |first1=J. |last2=Raven |first2=J. C. |last3=Court |first3=J. H. |origyear=1998 |year=2003 |title=Manual for Raven's Progressive Matrices and Vocabulary Scales |chapter=Section 1: General Overview |location=San Antonio, TX |publisher=Harcourt Assessment}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> is one of the most commonly used measures of fluid abilities. It is a non-verbal multiple choice test. Participants have to complete a series of drawings by identifying relevant features based on the spatial organization of an array of objects, and choosing one object that matches one or more of the identified features.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.21.001.2009 |title=MGluR<sub>1</sub> Receptors Contribute to Non-Purinergic Slow Excitatory Transmission to Submucosal VIP Neurons of Guinea-Pig Ileum |year=2009 |last1=Bornstein |first1=Joel C. |last2=Foong |first2=Jaime Pei Pei |journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience |volume=3 |pmid=20582273 |pmc=2695390 |pages=46}}</ref> This task assesses the ability to consider one or more relationships between mental representations or ''relational reasoning.'' ''Propositional analogies'' and semantic decision tasks are also used to assess relational reasoning.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.09.008.2007 |title=Neural correlates of fluid reasoning in children and adults |year=2007 |last1=Wright |journal=Frontiers in Human Neuroscience |pmid=18958222 |pmc=2525981 |first1=Samantha B. |last2=Matlen |first2=Bryan J. |last3=Baym |first3=Carol L. |last4=Ferrer |first4=Emilio |last5=Bunge |first5=Silvia A. |volume=1 |pages=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.01.003.2009 |title=Fluid reasoning and the developing brain |year=2009 |last1=Ferrer |first1=Emilio |last2=O'Hare |first2=Elizabeth D. |last3=Bunge |first3=Silvia A. |journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=46\u201351 |pmid=19753096 |pmc=2858618}}</ref>\n\nStandardized IQ tests such as those used in psychoeducational [[Psychological assessment|assessment]] also include tests of fluid intelligence. In the [[Woodcock-Johnson Tests of Cognitive Abilities]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=R. W. |last2=McGrew |first2=K. S. |last3=Mather |first3=N |year=2001 |title=Woodcock Johnson III |location=Itasca, IL |publisher=Riverside}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Gf is assessed by two tests: Concept Formation (Test 5) in the Standard Battery and Analysis Synthesis (Test 15) in the Extended Battery. On Concept Formation tasks, the individual has to apply concepts by inferring the underlying \"rules\" for solving visual puzzles that are presented in increasing levels of difficulty. Individuals at the preschool level have to point to a shape that is different from others in a set. As the level of difficulty increases, individuals increasingly demonstrate an understanding of what constitutes a key difference (or the \"rule\") for solving puzzles involving one to one comparisons, and on later items identifying common differences among a set of items. For more difficult items, individuals need to understand the concept of \"and\" (e.g. solution must have some of this and some of that) and the concept of \"or\" (e.g. to be inside a box, the item must be either this or that). The most difficult items require fluid transformations and cognitive shifting between the various types of concept puzzles that the examinee has worked with previously.<ref name=\"Schrank\">{{cite book |last1=Schrank |first1=F. A. |last2=Flanagan |first2=D. P. |year=2003 |title=WJ III Clinical use and interpretation. Scientist-practitioner perspectives |location=San Diego, CA |publisher=Academic Press}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nConcept Formation tasks assess inductive reasoning ability. In the Analysis-Synthesis test, the individual has to learn and orally state the solutions to incomplete logic puzzles that mimic a miniature mathematics system. The test also contains some of the features involved in using symbolic formulations in other fields such as chemistry and logic. The individual is presented with a set of logic rules, a \"key\" that is used to solve the puzzles. The individual has to determine the missing colors within each of the puzzles using the key. Complex items present puzzles that require two or more sequential mental manipulations of the key to derive a final solution. Increasingly difficult items involve a mix of puzzles that require fluid shifts in deduction, logic, and inference.<ref name=\"Schrank\" /> Analysis Synthesis tasks assess general sequential reasoning.\n\nIn the [[Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children]]-IV (WISC IV),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wechsler |first1=D. |year=2003 |title=WISC-IV technical and interpretive manual |location=San Antonio, TX |publisher=Psychological Corporation}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> the Perceptual Reasoning Index contains two subtests that assess Gf: Matrix Reasoning, which involves induction and deduction, and Picture Concepts, which involves induction.<ref name=\"Flanagan\">{{cite book |last1=Flanagan |first1=D. P. |last2=Kaufman |first2=A. S. |year=2004 |title=Essentials of WISC-IV assessment |url=https://archive.org/details/essentialsofwisc0000flan |url-access=registration |location=Hoboken, NJ |publisher=John Wiley}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> In the Picture Concepts task, children are presented a series of pictures on two or three rows and asked which pictures (one from each row) belong together based on some common characteristic. This task assesses the child's ability to discover the underlying characteristic (e.g. rule, concept, trend, class membership) that governs a set of materials. Matrix Reasoning also tests this ability as well as the ability to start with stated rules, premises, or conditions and to engage in one or more steps to reach a solution to a novel problem (deduction). In the Matrix Reasoning test, children are presented a series or sequence of pictures with one picture missing. Their task is to choose the picture that fits the series or sequence from an array of five options. Since Matrix Reasoning and Picture Concepts involve the use of visual stimuli and do not require expressive language, they are considered to be non-verbal tests of Gf.<ref name=\"Flanagan\" />\n\nWithin the corporate environment, fluid intelligence is a predictor of a person's capacity to work well in environments characterised by complexity, uncertainty, and ambiguity. The Cognitive Process Profile (CPP) measures  a person's fluid intelligence and cognitive processes. It maps these against suitable work environments according to [[Elliott Jacques]] Stratified Systems Theory.\n\n==Development and physiology==\n\nFluid intelligence, like [[reaction time]], typically peaks in young adulthood and then steadily declines. This decline may be related to local atrophy of the brain in the right cerebellum.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1440-1819.2005.01330.x |title=Intellect declines in healthy elderly subjects and cerebellum |year=2005 |last1=Lee |first1=Jun-Young |last2=Lyoo |first2=In Kyoon|last3=Kim |first3=Seon-Uk |last4=Jang |first4=Hong-Suk |last5=Lee |first5=Dong-Woo |last6=Jeon |first6=Hong-Jin |last7=Park |first7=Sang-Chul |last8=Cho |first8=Maeng Je |journal=Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences |volume=59 |pages=45\u201351 |pmid=15679539 |issue=1 |hdl=10371/27902}}</ref> Other researchers have suggested that a lack of practice, along with age-related changes in the brain, may contribute to the decline.<ref name=Cavanaugh>{{cite book |last1=Cavanaugh |first1=J. C. |last2=Blanchard-Fields |first2=F |year=2006 |title=Adult development and aging |edition=5th |location=Belmont, CA |publisher=Wadsworth Publishing/Thomson Learning |isbn=978-0-534-52066-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/adultdevelopment00john }}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Crystallized intelligence typically increases gradually, stays relatively stable across most of adulthood, and then begins to decline after age 65.<ref name=\"Cavanaugh\" /> The exact peak age of cognitive skills remains elusive, since it depends on both the skill measurement as well as on the survey design. Cross-sectional data shows typically an earlier onset of cognitive decline in comparison with longitudinal data. The former may be confounded due to cohort effects while the latter may be biased due to prior test experiences.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1787/5k9csvw87ckh-en |title=Ageing and Skills |series=OECD Education Working Papers |year=2012 |last1=Desjardins |first1=Richard |last2=Warnke |first2=Arne Jonas|hdl=10419/57089 |url=https://www.econstor.eu/bitstream/10419/57089/1/2012_Desjardins_Warnke.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Working memory]] capacity is closely related to fluid intelligence, and has been proposed to account for individual differences in Gf.<ref name=gfasWorkingMemory>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0160-2896(05)80012-1 |title=Reasoning ability is (little more than) working-memory capacity?! |year=1990 |last1=Kyllonen |first1=Patrick C. |last2=Christal |first2=Raymond E. |journal=Intelligence |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=389\u2013433}}</ref>\n\n== Improving fluid intelligence with training on working memory ==\n\nAccording to David Geary, Gf and Gc can be traced to two separate brain systems. Fluid intelligence involves both the [[dorsolateral prefrontal cortex]], the [[anterior cingulate cortex]], and other systems related to attention and short-term memory. Crystallized intelligence appears to be a function of brain regions that involve the storage and usage of long-term memories, such as the [[hippocampus]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Geary |first1=D. C. |year=2005 |url=http://www.apa.org/pubs/books/4318015.aspx| title=The origin of mind: Evolution of brain, cognition, and general intelligence |location=Washington, DC |publisher=American Psychological Association}}</ref>\n\nSome researchers question whether the results of training are long lasting and transferable, especially when these techniques are used by healthy children and adults without cognitive deficiencies.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Failure of Working Memory Training to Enhance Cognition or Intelligence | author=Todd W. Thompson |year=2013 | journal=PLoS ONE|issue=5|pages = e63614|volume=8|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0063614 | pmid=23717453 | pmc=3661602 }}</ref> A meta-analytical review conducted by researchers from the [[University of Oslo]] in 2012 concluded that \"memory training programs appear to produce short-term, specific training effects that do not generalize.\"<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/a0028228 |title=Is Working Memory Training Effective? A Meta-Analytic Review |year=2012 |last1=Melby-Lerv\u00e5g |first1=Monica |last2=Hulme |first2=Charles |journal=Developmental Psychology |pmid=22612437 |volume=49 |issue=2 |pages=270\u201391|url=http://www.apa.org/pubs/journals/releases/dev-49-2-270.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn a study using four individual experiments, 70 participants (36 of them female, all with a mean age of 25.6) recruited from the University of Bern community, Susanne M. Jaeggi and her colleagues at the University of Michigan found that healthy young adults who practiced a demanding working memory task ([[dual n-back|dual <var>n</var>-back]], a task that has strong face validity, has received some criticism regarding its construct validity and is in widespread use as a measure of working memory) approximately 25 minutes per day for between 8 and 19 days had statistically significant increases in their scores on a matrix test of fluid intelligence taken before and after the training than a control group who did not do any training at all.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.0801268105 |title=Improving fluid intelligence with training on working memory |year=2008 |last1=Jaeggi |first1=Susanne M. |last2=Buschkuehl |first2=Martin |last3=Jonides |first3=John |last4=Perrig |first4=Walter J. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=105 |issue=19 |pages=6829\u201333 |jstor=25461885 |bibcode=2008PNAS..105.6829J |pmid=18443283 |pmc=2383929}}</ref>\n\nA further examination of these findings was published in 2008 in the Proceedings of the Nation Academy of Sciences of the United States of America. Summarizing findings in the study as evidence that demonstrates that \"fluid intelligence is trainable to a significant and meaningful degree.\"\n\nAttention is drawn to the limitations of these results and the need for specific follow up inquiry. Robert J. Sternberg comments that \"it is unclear to what extent the results can be generalized to other working-memory tasks\" and  states \"it would be useful to show that the training transfers to success in meaningful behaviours that extend beyond the realm of psychometric testing\". Sternberg asserts that ability level of the test participants is not necessarily examining a wide range of ability levels, or \"address whether the training is durable over extended periods of time [and not only] \"fleeting.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |pmc = 2383939|year = 2008|last1 = Sternberg|first1 = R. J.|title = Increasing fluid intelligence is possible after all|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume = 105|issue = 19|pages = 6791\u20136792|pmid = 18474863|doi = 10.1073/pnas.0803396105}}</ref>\n\nA second study conducted at the University of Technology in Hangzhou, China, supports Jaeggi's results independently. After student subjects were given a 10-day training regimen based on the dual n-back working memory theory, the students were tested on [[Raven's Progressive Matrices|Raven's Standard Progressive Matrices]]. Their scores were found to have increased significantly.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/ICISE.2009.1124 |chapter-url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1727465 | chapter=Study on Improving Fluid Intelligence through Cognitive Training System Based on Gabor Stimulus |title=2009 First International Conference on Information Science and Engineering |year=2009 |last1=Qiu |first1=Feiyue |last2=Wei |first2=Qinqin |last3=Zhao |first3=Liying |last4=Lin |first4=Lifang |isbn=978-1-4244-4909-5 |pages=3459\u201362}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent studies on n-back, namely by Chooi & Thompson<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.intell.2012.07.004 |title=Working memory training does not improve intelligence in healthy young adults |year=2012 |last1=Chooi |first1=Weng-Tink |last2=Thompson |first2=Lee A. |journal=Intelligence |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=531\u201342}}</ref> and Redick et al.,<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=22708717 |year=2012 |last1=Redick |first1=Thomas S. |last2=Shipstead |first2=Zach |last3=Harrison |first3=Tyler L. |last4=Hicks |first4=Kenny L. |last5=Fried |first5=David E. |last6=Hambrick |first6=David Z. |last7=Kane |first7=Michael J. |last8=Engle |first8=Randall W. |title=No Evidence of Intelligence Improvement After Working Memory Training: A Randomized, Placebo-Controlled Study |doi=10.1037/a0029082 |journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: General |volume=142 |issue=2 |pages=359\u2013379}}</ref> do not support the findings of the Jaeggi study. Although participants' performance on the training task improved, these studies showed no significant improvement in the mental abilities tested, especially fluid intelligence and working memory capacity.\n\n==See also==\n*[[21st century skills]]\n*[[CHC theory]]\n*[[Deeper learning]]\n*[[General intelligence factor]]\n*[[John L. Horn]]\n*[[Intelligence]]\n*[[Malleability of intelligence]]\n*[[Nootropic]]\n*[[Outline of human intelligence]]\n*[[Raymond Cattell]]\n*[[Spatial intelligence (psychology)]]\n*[[Three stratum theory]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Human intelligence topics}}\n{{Evolutionary psychology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fluid And Crystallized Intelligence}}\n[[Category:Intelligence by type]]\n[[Category:Creativity]]\n[[Category:Intelligence]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=August 2019}}\n{{Confusing|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{short description|Factors of general intelligence}}\nAccording to the theory published in 1963 by the psychologist [[Raymond Cattell]],<ref name = \"Cattell & Horn\">Cattell, R. B. (1963). Theory of fluid and crystallized intelligence: A critical experiment. ''Journal of Educational Psychology, 54'', 1-22. doi:org/10.1037/h0046743</ref><ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VG85AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 Handbook of Human Intelligence]. CUP, 1982, p. 75.</ref><ref>Cattell, R. B. (1971). ''Abilities: Their structure, growth, and action''. New York: Houghton Mifflin. {{ISBN|0-395-04275-5}}.</ref> [[g factor (psychometrics)|general intelligence]] (''g'') is subdivided into '''fluid intelligence (''g''<sub>f</sub>)''' and '''crystallized intelligence (''g''<sub>c</sub>)'''. Fluid intelligence is the ability to  solve novel reasoning problems and is correlated with a number of important skills such as comprehension, problem solving, and learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Unsworth|first=Nash|last2=Fukuda|first2=Keisuke|last3=Awh|first3=Edward|last4=Vogel|first4=Edward K.|date=2014|title=Working memory and fluid intelligence: Capacity, attention control, and secondary memory retrieval|journal=Cognitive Psychology|language=en|volume=71|pages=1\u201326|doi=10.1016/j.cogpsych.2014.01.003|pmc=4484859|pmid=24531497}}</ref> Crystallized intelligence on the other hand is the ability to [[Deductive reasoning|deduce]] secondary relational abstractions by applying primary relational abstractions to each other.<ref name=\"Pseudointelligence\">Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action]. Elsevier, 1987, p. 294.</ref> However, the deduced relations among relations must be checked by fluid intelligence.<ref name=Cattell-1987-p294>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action]. Elsevier, 1987, p. 294.</ref>\n\nFluid intelligence depends on [[working memory]] capacity,<ref name=gfasWorkingMemory/> localized in the [[prefrontal cortex]].<ref name=FrontalityofWorkingMemory>Dehn, Milton J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j5ha-QRBHw8C&pg=PA69 Long-Term Memory Problems in Children and Adolescents] John Wiley & Sons, 2010, p. 69</ref> This region degenerates faster than other cortical regions in the course of aging and [[Encephalopathy|encephalopathies]].<ref name=Fuster>Fuster, Joaquin. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zuZlvNICdhUC&pg=PA44 The Prefrontal Cortex] Elsevier, 2008, p. 44</ref> Fluid intelligence peaks at around age 20, and then gradually declines.<ref>Cacioppo, John T.; Freberg, Laura. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=md8KAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT448 Discovering Psychology: The Science of Mind]. Cengage Learning, 2012, p. 448</ref>\n\n==History==\nFluid and crystallized intelligence were originally identified by [[Raymond Cattell]].<ref name = \"Cattell & Horn\"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Cattell |first=R. B. |year=1971 |title=Abilities: Their structure, growth, and action |location=New York |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |isbn=978-0-395-04275-5}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Concepts of fluid and crystallized intelligence were further developed by Cattell's student, [[John L. Horn]].\n\nSome researchers have linked the theory of fluid and crystallized abilities to [[Piaget's theory of cognitive development]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2190/AG.2.1.b |title=Piagetian Theory and the Aging Process: Extensions and Speculations |year=1971 |last1=Papalia |first1=D. |last2=Fitzgerald |first2=J. |last3=Hooper |first3=F. H. |journal=The International Journal of Aging and Human Development |volume=2 |pages=3\u201320}}</ref><ref>Schonfeld, I.S. (1986). The Genevan and Cattell-Horn conceptions of intelligence compared: The early implementation of numerical solution aids. ''Developmental Psychology, 22'', 204-212. [https://academicworks.cuny.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1278&context=gc_pubs]</ref> Fluid ability and Piaget's operative intelligence both concern logical thinking and the eduction of relations. Crystallized ability and Piaget's treatment of everyday learning reflect the impress of experience. Like fluid ability's relation to crystallized intelligence, Piaget's operativity is considered to be prior to, and ultimately provides the foundation for, everyday learning.\n\n==Fluid versus crystallized==\n*Fluid intelligence is [[Inductive reasoning|inductive]]<ref name=Insight2>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA294 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, p. 294</ref><ref name=Cattell-1987-p542>Cattell, R. B. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=flX770mG2HcC&pg=PA542 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, p. 542</ref> ([[Visuospatial function|visuospatial]]<ref name=Rogers>Rogers, Barrie. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JX8QAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Spatial+ability+(k)+was+shown+to+be+closely+related+to+fluid+intelligence+(gf).%22 Human Personality: Towards a Unified Theory] Vantage Press, 1972, p. 96</ref><ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rqpCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA39&dq=%22Tasks+with+a+heavy+spatial+component+are+correlated+with+measures+of+fluid+intelligence,+sometimes+almost+perfectly%22 The Nature of Human Intelligence] CUP, 2018, p. 39</ref>) intelligence,<ref name=Kassin>Kassin, Saul M. [https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Shown+on+the+right+are+the+results+of+four+measures:+two+involving+fluid+intelligence+(spatial+ability+and+inductive+reasoning)+and+two+involving+crystallized+intelligence+(verbal+ability+and+numeric+ability)%22&num=10 Psychology] Prentice Hall, 1998, p. 424</ref> which is [[Synergy|synergetic]], because its conclusions do not mechanically follow from their premises.\n*Crystallized intelligence is [[Deductive reasoning|deductive]]<ref name=Insight2/><ref name=Cattell-1987-p542/> (verbal<ref>Sternberg, Robert J. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jnEYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Verbal+ability+is+also+an+excellent+measure+of+crystallized+intelligence%22 Encyclopedia of Human Intelligence] Vol. 1, Macmillan, 1995, p. 1107</ref> and numeric) intelligence,<ref name=Kassin/> which is [[Synergy|asynergetic]], because its conclusions mechanically follow from their premises.\n\nPsychologist [[Geoffrey Miller (psychologist)|Geoffrey Miller]] has argued that human intelligence and capacities for the [[cultural universal]]s of [[language]], [[music]], and [[art]] are unnecessarily sophisticated for the [[Survival of the fittest|survival]] needs of [[hunter-gatherer]]s and has argued instead that the evolution of general intelligence occurred by sexual selection rather than [[natural selection]],<ref name=\"Miller 2000\">{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Geoffrey F.|author-link=Geoffrey Miller (psychologist)|title=The Mating Mind: How Sexual Choice Shaped the Evolution of Human Nature|place=New York|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|year=2000|edition=1st|isbn=978-0385495165|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/matingmind00geof}}</ref> while philosopher [[Denis Dutton]] also argued that the [[Evolutionary aesthetics|human capacity for aesthetics]] evolved by sexual selection.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dutton|first=Denis|author-link=Denis Dutton|title=The Art Instinct: Beauty, Pleasure, and Human Evolution|year=2009|pages=135\u2013163|place=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury Press]]|isbn=978-1596914018}}</ref> In 2007, behavioral scientist [[Daniel Nettle]] did statistical analysis relating [[Empathizing\u2013systemizing theory|empathizing\u2013systemizing theory]] as proposed by clinical psychologist [[Simon Baron-Cohen]] to the [[Big Five personality traits]] and found that the empathizing quotient had a 0.75 correlation with the [[Agreeableness|agreeability factor]] (with equivalent values on between-sex measurements), while finding that the systemizing quotient held only a 0.37 correlation to [[openness to experience]] and a 0.30 correlation with [[conscientiousness]].<ref>{{cite article|last=Nettle|first=Daniel|title=Empathizing and systemizing: What are they, and what do they contribute to our understanding of psychological sex differences?|journal=[[British Journal of Psychology]]|year=2007|volume=98|pages=237\u2013255|pmid=17456271|doi=10.1348/000712606X117612}}</ref> Nettle cites research by occupational psychologist [[Adrian Furnham]] that showed openness to experience to be positively related to general intelligence and that openness to experience is most consistently related to [[Verbal reasoning|verbal intelligence]],<ref>{{cite article|last1=Moutafi|first1=Joanna|last2=Furnham|first2=Adrian|author-link2=Adrian Furnham|last3=Crump|first3=John|title=Demographic and Personality Predictors of Intelligence: A Study Using the Neo Personality Inventory and the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator|journal=[[European Journal of Personality]]|publisher=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]]|year=2003|volume=17|issue=1|pages=79\u201394|doi=10.1002/per.471}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|last1=Moutafi|first1=Joanna|last2=Furnham|first2=Adrian|author-link2=Adrian Furnham|last3=Paltiel|first3=Laurence|title=Can Personality Factors Predict Intelligence?|journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=2005|volume=38|issue=5|pages=1021\u20131033|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2004.06.023}}</ref> Nettle concluded that the systemizing quotient was capturing some aspect of intelligence rather than personality. that  In 2007, a [[meta-analysis]] of research on correlations between general intelligence and the Big Five showed openness to experience to have the highest correlation (0.22).<ref>{{cite book|last1=von Stumm|first1=Sophie|last2=Chamorro-Premuzic|first2=Tomas|last3=Ackerman|first3=Phillip L.|year=2011|chapter=Re-visiting intelligence-personality associations: Vindicating intellectual investment|editor-first1=Tomas|editor-last1=Chamorro-Premuzic|editor-first2=Sophie|editor-last2=von Stumm|editor-first3=Adrian|editor-last3=Furnham|title=Handbook of Individual Differences|place=[[Chichester]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]|publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]]|isbn=978-1119050308}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Judge|first1=T. A.|last2=Jackson|first2=C. L.|last3=Shaw|first3=J. C.|last4=Scott|first4=B. A.|last5=Rich|first5=B. L.|year=2007|title=Self-efficacy and work-related performance: The integral role of individual differences|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0c0fb061ac17f23520773efc68b539ab35e9a358|journal=[[Journal of Applied Psychology]]|volume=92|issue=1|pages=107\u2013127|doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.1.107|pmid=17227155}}</ref> Psychologists Akio Wakabayashi and Hiromi Kawashima, using the [[HEXACO model of personality structure]], replicated Nettle's openness to experience correlation (0.44) but found the empathizing quotient more strongly correlated to the [[Extraversion and introversion|extraversion factor]] (0.32) than the agreeability factor (0.17).<ref>{{cite article|last1=Wakabayashi|first1=Akio|last2=Kawashima|first2=Hiromi|title=Is empathizing in the E\u2013S theory similar to agreeableness? The relationship between the EQ and SQ and major personality domains|journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|year=2015|volume=76|pages=88\u201393|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S019188691400662X}}</ref>\n\nEach type of crystallized intelligence is independent of the other (increasing a student's proficiency in Latin does not increase the student's proficiency in algebra), but to a high degree dependent on the individual's fluid intelligence (students proficient in Latin tend to be proficient in algebra, too, because people with a high ''g''<sub>f</sub> tend to acquire more ''g''<sub>c</sub>-knowledge and at faster rates), and, to a lesser degree, on the quality of the learning environment (''e.g.'', the quality of available books).<ref>Cattell, R. B. [https://archive.org/details/intelligenceitss00catt/page/138 Intelligence: Its Structure, Growth and Action] Elsevier, 1987, pp. 138\u201339</ref>\n\n==Factor structure==\n\nFluid intelligence generally correlates with measures of abstract reasoning and puzzle solving. Crystallized intelligence correlates with abilities that depend on knowledge and experience, such as vocabulary, general information, and analogies. Paul Kline identified a number of factors that shared a correlation of at least r=.60 with ''g''<sub>f</sub> and ''g''<sub>c</sub>.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kline |first1=P. |year=1998 |title=The new psychometrics: Science, psychology and measurement |location=London |publisher=Routledge}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Factors with {{clarify span|median loadings|date=February 2013}} of greater than 0.6 on ''g''<sub>f</sub> included induction, visualization, quantitative reasoning, and ideational fluency. Factors with median loadings of greater than 0.6 on ''g''<sub>c</sub> included verbal ability, language development, reading comprehension, sequential reasoning, and general information. It may be suggested that tests of intelligence may not be able to truly reflect levels of fluid intelligence. Some authors have suggested that unless an individual was truly interested in the problem presented, the cognitive work required may not be performed because of a lack of interest.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=1175249 |doi=10.3102/0013189X018002005 |title=Meaning and Values in Test Validation: The Science and Ethics of Assessment |year=1989 |last1=Messick |first1=Samuel |journal=Educational Researcher |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=5\u201311}}</ref> These authors contend that a low score on tests which are intended to measure fluid intelligence may reflect more a lack of interest in the tasks themselves rather than any sort of inability to complete the tasks successfully.\n\n==Measurement of fluid intelligence==\nThere are various measures that assess fluid intelligence. The [[Cattell Culture Fair III|Cattell Culture Fair IQ test]], the [[Raven's Progressive Matrices|Raven Progressive Matrices]] (RPM), and the performance subscale of the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale|WAIS]] are measures of Gf. The RPM<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raven |first1=J. |last2=Raven |first2=J. C. |last3=Court |first3=J. H. |origyear=1998 |year=2003 |title=Manual for Raven's Progressive Matrices and Vocabulary Scales |chapter=Section 1: General Overview |location=San Antonio, TX |publisher=Harcourt Assessment}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> is one of the most commonly used measures of fluid abilities. It is a non-verbal multiple choice test. Participants have to complete a series of drawings by identifying relevant features based on the spatial organization of an array of objects, and choosing one object that matches one or more of the identified features.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.21.001.2009 |title=MGluR<sub>1</sub> Receptors Contribute to Non-Purinergic Slow Excitatory Transmission to Submucosal VIP Neurons of Guinea-Pig Ileum |year=2009 |last1=Bornstein |first1=Joel C. |last2=Foong |first2=Jaime Pei Pei |journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience |volume=3 |pmid=20582273 |pmc=2695390 |pages=46}}</ref> This task assesses the ability to consider one or more relationships between mental representations or ''relational reasoning.'' ''Propositional analogies'' and semantic decision tasks are also used to assess relational reasoning.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.09.008.2007 |title=Neural correlates of fluid reasoning in children and adults |year=2007 |last1=Wright |journal=Frontiers in Human Neuroscience |pmid=18958222 |pmc=2525981 |first1=Samantha B. |last2=Matlen |first2=Bryan J. |last3=Baym |first3=Carol L. |last4=Ferrer |first4=Emilio |last5=Bunge |first5=Silvia A. |volume=1 |pages=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3389/neuro.01.003.2009 |title=Fluid reasoning and the developing brain |year=2009 |last1=Ferrer |first1=Emilio |last2=O'Hare |first2=Elizabeth D. |last3=Bunge |first3=Silvia A. |journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=46\u201351 |pmid=19753096 |pmc=2858618}}</ref>\n\nStandardized IQ tests such as those used in psychoeducational [[Psychological assessment|assessment]] also include tests of fluid intelligence. In the [[Woodcock-Johnson Tests of Cognitive Abilities]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woodcock |first1=R. W. |last2=McGrew |first2=K. S. |last3=Mather |first3=N |year=2001 |title=Woodcock Johnson III |location=Itasca, IL |publisher=Riverside}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Gf is assessed by two tests: Concept Formation (Test 5) in the Standard Battery and Analysis Synthesis (Test 15) in the Extended Battery. On Concept Formation tasks, the individual has to apply concepts by inferring the underlying \"rules\" for solving visual puzzles that are presented in increasing levels of difficulty. Individuals at the preschool level have to point to a shape that is different from others in a set. As the level of difficulty increases, individuals increasingly demonstrate an understanding of what constitutes a key difference (or the \"rule\") for solving puzzles involving one to one comparisons, and on later items identifying common differences among a set of items. For more difficult items, individuals need to understand the concept of \"and\" (e.g. solution must have some of this and some of that) and the concept of \"or\" (e.g. to be inside a box, the item must be either this or that). The most difficult items require fluid transformations and cognitive shifting between the various types of concept puzzles that the examinee has worked with previously.<ref name=\"Schrank\">{{cite book |last1=Schrank |first1=F. A. |last2=Flanagan |first2=D. P. |year=2003 |title=WJ III Clinical use and interpretation. Scientist-practitioner perspectives |location=San Diego, CA |publisher=Academic Press}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nConcept Formation tasks assess inductive reasoning ability. In the Analysis-Synthesis test, the individual has to learn and orally state the solutions to incomplete logic puzzles that mimic a miniature mathematics system. The test also contains some of the features involved in using symbolic formulations in other fields such as chemistry and logic. The individual is presented with a set of logic rules, a \"key\" that is used to solve the puzzles. The individual has to determine the missing colors within each of the puzzles using the key. Complex items present puzzles that require two or more sequential mental manipulations of the key to derive a final solution. Increasingly difficult items involve a mix of puzzles that require fluid shifts in deduction, logic, and inference.<ref name=\"Schrank\" /> Analysis Synthesis tasks assess general sequential reasoning.\n\nIn the [[Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children]]-IV (WISC IV),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wechsler |first1=D. |year=2003 |title=WISC-IV technical and interpretive manual |location=San Antonio, TX |publisher=Psychological Corporation}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> the Perceptual Reasoning Index contains two subtests that assess Gf: Matrix Reasoning, which involves induction and deduction, and Picture Concepts, which involves induction.<ref name=\"Flanagan\">{{cite book |last1=Flanagan |first1=D. P. |last2=Kaufman |first2=A. S. |year=2004 |title=Essentials of WISC-IV assessment |url=https://archive.org/details/essentialsofwisc0000flan |url-access=registration |location=Hoboken, NJ |publisher=John Wiley}}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> In the Picture Concepts task, children are presented a series of pictures on two or three rows and asked which pictures (one from each row) belong together based on some common characteristic. This task assesses the child's ability to discover the underlying characteristic (e.g. rule, concept, trend, class membership) that governs a set of materials. Matrix Reasoning also tests this ability as well as the ability to start with stated rules, premises, or conditions and to engage in one or more steps to reach a solution to a novel problem (deduction). In the Matrix Reasoning test, children are presented a series or sequence of pictures with one picture missing. Their task is to choose the picture that fits the series or sequence from an array of five options. Since Matrix Reasoning and Picture Concepts involve the use of visual stimuli and do not require expressive language, they are considered to be non-verbal tests of Gf.<ref name=\"Flanagan\" />\n\nWithin the corporate environment, fluid intelligence is a predictor of a person's capacity to work well in environments characterised by complexity, uncertainty, and ambiguity. The Cognitive Process Profile (CPP) measures  a person's fluid intelligence and cognitive processes. It maps these against suitable work environments according to [[Elliott Jacques]] Stratified Systems Theory.\n\n==Development and physiology==\n\nFluid intelligence, like [[reaction time]], typically peaks in young adulthood and then steadily declines. This decline may be related to local atrophy of the brain in the right cerebellum.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1440-1819.2005.01330.x |title=Intellect declines in healthy elderly subjects and cerebellum |year=2005 |last1=Lee |first1=Jun-Young |last2=Lyoo |first2=In Kyoon|last3=Kim |first3=Seon-Uk |last4=Jang |first4=Hong-Suk |last5=Lee |first5=Dong-Woo |last6=Jeon |first6=Hong-Jin |last7=Park |first7=Sang-Chul |last8=Cho |first8=Maeng Je |journal=Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences |volume=59 |pages=45\u201351 |pmid=15679539 |issue=1 |hdl=10371/27902}}</ref> Other researchers have suggested that a lack of practice, along with age-related changes in the brain, may contribute to the decline.<ref name=Cavanaugh>{{cite book |last1=Cavanaugh |first1=J. C. |last2=Blanchard-Fields |first2=F |year=2006 |title=Adult development and aging |edition=5th |location=Belmont, CA |publisher=Wadsworth Publishing/Thomson Learning |isbn=978-0-534-52066-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/adultdevelopment00john }}{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Crystallized intelligence typically increases gradually, stays relatively stable across most of adulthood, and then begins to decline after age 65.<ref name=\"Cavanaugh\" /> The exact peak age of cognitive skills remains elusive, since it depends on both the skill measurement as well as on the survey design. Cross-sectional data shows typically an earlier onset of cognitive decline in comparison with longitudinal data. The former may be confounded due to cohort effects while the latter may be biased due to prior test experiences.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1787/5k9csvw87ckh-en |title=Ageing and Skills |series=OECD Education Working Papers |year=2012 |last1=Desjardins |first1=Richard |last2=Warnke |first2=Arne Jonas|hdl=10419/57089 |url=https://www.econstor.eu/bitstream/10419/57089/1/2012_Desjardins_Warnke.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Working memory]] capacity is closely related to fluid intelligence, and has been proposed to account for individual differences in Gf.<ref name=gfasWorkingMemory>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0160-2896(05)80012-1 |title=Reasoning ability is (little more than) working-memory capacity?! |year=1990 |last1=Kyllonen |first1=Patrick C. |last2=Christal |first2=Raymond E. |journal=Intelligence |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=389\u2013433}}</ref>\n\n== Improving fluid intelligence with training on working memory ==\n\nAccording to David Geary, Gf and Gc can be traced to two separate brain systems. Fluid intelligence involves both the [[dorsolateral prefrontal cortex]], the [[anterior cingulate cortex]], and other systems related to attention and short-term memory. Crystallized intelligence appears to be a function of brain regions that involve the storage and usage of long-term memories, such as the [[hippocampus]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Geary |first1=D. C. |year=2005 |url=http://www.apa.org/pubs/books/4318015.aspx| title=The origin of mind: Evolution of brain, cognition, and general intelligence |location=Washington, DC |publisher=American Psychological Association}}</ref>\n\nSome researchers question whether the results of training are long lasting and transferable, especially when these techniques are used by healthy children and adults without cognitive deficiencies.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Failure of Working Memory Training to Enhance Cognition or Intelligence | author=Todd W. Thompson |year=2013 | journal=PLoS ONE|issue=5|pages = e63614|volume=8|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0063614 | pmid=23717453 | pmc=3661602 }}</ref> A meta-analytical review conducted by researchers from the [[University of Oslo]] in 2012 concluded that \"memory training programs appear to produce short-term, specific training effects that do not generalize.\"<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/a0028228 |title=Is Working Memory Training Effective? A Meta-Analytic Review |year=2012 |last1=Melby-Lerv\u00e5g |first1=Monica |last2=Hulme |first2=Charles |journal=Developmental Psychology |pmid=22612437 |volume=49 |issue=2 |pages=270\u201391|url=http://www.apa.org/pubs/journals/releases/dev-49-2-270.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn a study using four individual experiments, 70 participants (36 of them female, all with a mean age of 25.6) recruited from the University of Bern community, Susanne M. Jaeggi and her colleagues at the University of Michigan found that healthy young adults who practiced a demanding working memory task ([[dual n-back|dual <var>n</var>-back]], a task that has strong face validity, has received some criticism regarding its construct validity and is in widespread use as a measure of working memory) approximately 25 minutes per day for between 8 and 19 days had statistically significant increases in their scores on a matrix test of fluid intelligence taken before and after the training than a control group who did not do any training at all.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.0801268105 |title=Improving fluid intelligence with training on working memory |year=2008 |last1=Jaeggi |first1=Susanne M. |last2=Buschkuehl |first2=Martin |last3=Jonides |first3=John |last4=Perrig |first4=Walter J. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=105 |issue=19 |pages=6829\u201333 |jstor=25461885 |bibcode=2008PNAS..105.6829J |pmid=18443283 |pmc=2383929}}</ref>\n\nA further examination of these findings was published in 2008 in the Proceedings of the Nation Academy of Sciences of the United States of America. Summarizing findings in the study as evidence that demonstrates that \"fluid intelligence is trainable to a significant and meaningful degree.\"\n\nAttention is drawn to the limitations of these results and the need for specific follow up inquiry. Robert J. Sternberg comments that \"it is unclear to what extent the results can be generalized to other working-memory tasks\" and  states \"it would be useful to show that the training transfers to success in meaningful behaviours that extend beyond the realm of psychometric testing\". Sternberg asserts that ability level of the test participants is not necessarily examining a wide range of ability levels, or \"address whether the training is durable over extended periods of time [and not only] \"fleeting.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |pmc = 2383939|year = 2008|last1 = Sternberg|first1 = R. J.|title = Increasing fluid intelligence is possible after all|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume = 105|issue = 19|pages = 6791\u20136792|pmid = 18474863|doi = 10.1073/pnas.0803396105}}</ref>\n\nA second study conducted at the University of Technology in Hangzhou, China, supports Jaeggi's results independently. After student subjects were given a 10-day training regimen based on the dual n-back working memory theory, the students were tested on [[Raven's Progressive Matrices|Raven's Standard Progressive Matrices]]. Their scores were found to have increased significantly.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/ICISE.2009.1124 |chapter-url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1727465 | chapter=Study on Improving Fluid Intelligence through Cognitive Training System Based on Gabor Stimulus |title=2009 First International Conference on Information Science and Engineering |year=2009 |last1=Qiu |first1=Feiyue |last2=Wei |first2=Qinqin |last3=Zhao |first3=Liying |last4=Lin |first4=Lifang |isbn=978-1-4244-4909-5 |pages=3459\u201362}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent studies on n-back, namely by Chooi & Thompson<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.intell.2012.07.004 |title=Working memory training does not improve intelligence in healthy young adults |year=2012 |last1=Chooi |first1=Weng-Tink |last2=Thompson |first2=Lee A. |journal=Intelligence |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=531\u201342}}</ref> and Redick et al.,<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=22708717 |year=2012 |last1=Redick |first1=Thomas S. |last2=Shipstead |first2=Zach |last3=Harrison |first3=Tyler L. |last4=Hicks |first4=Kenny L. |last5=Fried |first5=David E. |last6=Hambrick |first6=David Z. |last7=Kane |first7=Michael J. |last8=Engle |first8=Randall W. |title=No Evidence of Intelligence Improvement After Working Memory Training: A Randomized, Placebo-Controlled Study |doi=10.1037/a0029082 |journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: General |volume=142 |issue=2 |pages=359\u2013379}}</ref> do not support the findings of the Jaeggi study. Although participants' performance on the training task improved, these studies showed no significant improvement in the mental abilities tested, especially fluid intelligence and working memory capacity.\n\n==See also==\n*[[21st century skills]]\n*[[CHC theory]]\n*[[Deeper learning]]\n*[[General intelligence factor]]\n*[[John L. Horn]]\n*[[Intelligence]]\n*[[Malleability of intelligence]]\n*[[Nootropic]]\n*[[Outline of human intelligence]]\n*[[Raymond Cattell]]\n*[[Spatial intelligence (psychology)]]\n*[[Three stratum theory]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Human intelligence topics}}\n{{Evolutionary psychology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fluid And Crystallized Intelligence}}\n[[Category:Intelligence by type]]\n[[Category:Creativity]]\n[[Category:Intelligence]]\n", "name_user": "CommonKnowledgeCreator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFluid versus crystallized:Removed duplicative name usage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_and_crystallized_intelligence"}
{"title_page": "Akala (rapper)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Akala\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Akala crop 2014.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Akala in 2014\n| birth_name       = Kingslee James McLean Daley\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1983|12|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]], England\n| origin           = [[Kentish Town]], [[London]], England\n| death_date       = \n| genre            = [[British hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], poet, journalist, songwriter and activist\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present\n| label            = Immovable Ltd (Illa State Records)\n| associated_acts  = [[Lowkey]]<br>[[Ms. Dynamite]]<br/>[[Durrty Goodz]]<br/>[[Black the Ripper]]\n| website          = {{url|http://akalamusic.com}}\n}}\n'''Kingslee James McLean Daley''' (born 1 December 1983), better known by the stage name '''Akala''', is a British rapper, journalist, author, activist and poet.\n\nHe is originally from [[Kentish Town]], north [[London]]. In 2006, he was voted the Best Hip Hop Act at the [[Music of Black Origin Awards|MOBO Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/akala-mn0000560354/biography|title=Akala|author=Chris True|work=AllMusic}}</ref> and has been included on the annual ''[[Powerlist]]'' of the 100 most influential Black British people in the UK. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mills |first1=Kelly-Ann |title=Raheem Sterling joins Meghan and Stormzy in top 100 most influential black Brits |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/black-powerlist-2020-raheem-sterling-20721033 |website=mirror |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDaley was born in [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]], in 1983 to a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother and [[Jamaica]]n father who separated before he was born and grew up with his mother \"in the cliched, single-parent working-class family,\"<ref>Daley quote from his book Natives.</ref> in [[Kentish Town]], north London.<ref>Kate Mossman, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/02/akala-thieves-banquet-rap-interview \"Akala: Dynamite by any other name\u2026\"], ''[[The Observer]]'', 2 June 2013.</ref><ref>Brian Rose, [https://londonrealacademy.com/fight-the-power-akala-and-the-power-of-the-word/ \"Fight the Power \u2014 Akala and the Power of the Word\"], London Real Academy, 20 October 2015.</ref> He remembers the day he realised that his mum was white,<ref>http://socialistreview.org.uk/438/natives</ref> and was embarrassed by her whiteness, and that she could \u201cnever really \u2018get it\u2019\u201d when it came to racism.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/akala-s-race-polemic-up-for-oldest-literary-prize-6xl7vq6f8</ref> Daley's older sister is rapper [[Ms. Dynamite]].\n\nHis stepdad was a stage manager at the [[Hackney Empire]] theatre, and he often visited it before his teens.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> He also attended pan-African Saturday school, stating \"I benefited massively from a specifically black community-led self-education tradition that we don\u2019t talk about very much because it doesn\u2019t fit with the image [of black families]\".<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> When accepting honorary degrees, he has said he \"would like to thank the entire Caribbean pan-African community that helped me through school and encouraged an intellectual curiosity and self development from a very young age.\"<ref>https://archive.voice-online.co.uk/article/akala-receives-honorary-doctorate</ref> \n\nAt age 6, Daley's state primary school put him in a special needs group for pupils with learning difficulties and English as a second language.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> Daley saw a friend attacked by a meat cleaver to the skull when he was 12, and carried a knife himself for a period<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> He went on to achieve ten [[GCSEs|GCSE]] and took maths a year early. He has said he \"was in the top 1 per cent of GCSEs in the country. [He] got 100 per cent in [his] English exam.\"<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> As a teenager, Daley focused on football, being on the schoolboy books of both [[West Ham United]] and [[AFC Wimbledon]], and dropped out of college.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> Daley did not attend university, but has said he often envies those who do.<ref>\"He told graduates: \u201cI can\u2019t lie, I often envy those of you who do get to go, people like you \u2026 who are about to remake the world, or at least this country. That\u2019s how serious these four years are. What will you do with the time you spent here and the education you have been privileged to be loaned by the rest of society?\u201d https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2018/07-31-akala-urges-graduates-develop-good-habits.aspx</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n===2003\u201309: Early years and breakthrough===\n[[File:Melodee and Akala.jpg|thumb|left|Akala (right) in 2009.]]\nDaley got his stage name from [[Acala]], a [[Buddhist]] term for \"immovable\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesituation.co.uk/ukartists/06/akala/akala.html |title=Akala interview on \"The Situation\" website |accessdate=21 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912013648/http://www.thesituation.co.uk/ukartists/06/akala/akala.html |archivedate=12 September 2012 }}</ref> and started releasing music in 2003 from his own independent music label, Illa State Records. He released his first mixtape,''The War Mixtape'', in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala (2) - The War Mixtape |url=https://www.discogs.com/Akala-The-War-Mixtape/release/1305358 |website=Discogs |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he released his first album, ''[[It's Not a Rumour]]''. This proved to be his breakthrough album, containing the single \"Shakespeare\" (a reference to his self-proclaimed title \"The Black Shakespeare\") which made the [[BBC Radio 1]] playlist.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Webb |first1=Adam |title=BBC - Music - Review of Akala - It's Not a Rumour |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/ddvr/ |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> His work was recognised with the [[Music of Black Origin Awards|MOBO Award]] for Best Hip Hop Act.<ref>{{cite web |title=MOBO Awards 2006 {{!}} MOBO Organisation |url=https://www.mobo.com/history/2006 |website=www.mobo.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally in 2006, a mixtape, ''A Little Darker'', was released under the name \"Illa State\", featuring Akala and his sister, [[Ms. Dynamite]], as well as cameo appearances by many other artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala (2) & Ms. Dynamite - A Little Darker EP |url=https://www.discogs.com/Akala-2-Ms-Dynamite-A-Little-Darker-EP/release/709575 |website=Discogs |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDaley appeared for a live session on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] where he was challenged to come up with a rap containing as many Shakespeare play titles as he could manage, he wrote and performed a minute-long rap containing 27 different Shakespeare play titles in under half an hour and later recorded these lyrics in the studio and turned it into the single \"Comedy Tragedy History\".<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Two - Shakespeare Live! From the RSC - Akala |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/2vCgZCVB5gPpNYCXCTWs1JS/akala |website=BBC |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Daley released his second album, ''[[Freedom Lasso]]'', containing the \"Comedy Tragedy History\" track. The song \"Love in my Eyes\" heavily sampled  [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]]' song \"[[Mittageisen|Love in a void]]\" with the voice of [[Siouxsie Sioux]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macpherson |first1=Alex |title=CD: Akala, Freedom Lasso |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/sep/28/urban.shopping |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=27 September 2007}}</ref> In 2008, ''The War Mixtape Vol. 2'' was released, along with an EP of acoustic remixes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala Releases His Long Awaited Mixtape Entitled The War Mixtape Vol 2 |url=https://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=42842 |website=Top40-Charts.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present: ''Doublethink'', ''Knowledge Is Power'', and beyond===\n[[File:Akala Hull Jazz Festival 2015.jpg|thumb|Akala at the [[Hull Jazz Festival]] 2015.]]\nDaley's third studio album, ''[[DoubleThink]]'', was released in 2010, and holds a strong theme of [[George Orwell]]'s popular novel ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala: Doublethink Interview (video) |url=https://www.orwellfoundation.com/the-orwell-foundation/orwell/library/akala-doublethink-interview-video/ |website=The Orwell Foundation |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> ''DoubleThink'' contains tracks such as \"Find No Enemy\" and \"Yours and My Children\" detailing some of the sights he saw on his trip to Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andrews |first1=Charlotte Richardson |title=Brit-hop: 10 of the best |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/jul/09/brit-hop-10-of-the-best |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=9 July 2014}}</ref> In November 2010, Daley headlined a live performance at the [[British Library]], to launch the \"Evolving English\" exhibition and featured performances by British poet [[Zena Edwards]], comedian [[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]] and British rapper [[Lowkey]] which also included Daley taking part in a hip hop panel discussion alongside [[Saul Williams]], U.S professor [[MK Asante]] and Lowkey.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Love |first1=Emma |title=Hip-hop deciphered at the British Library |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/hip-hop-deciphered-at-the-british-library-2143735.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=26 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Evolving English One Language Many Voices80 |url=https://www.bl.uk/press-releases/2010/november/evolving-english-one-language-many-voices80 |website=The British Library |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Daley appeared on [[Charlie Sloth]]'s show on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|Radio 1Xtra]] on 18 July 2011, performing \"Fire in the Booth\", and after the great reception it received he returned again in May 2012 and provided \"Part 2\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJOp1CqzaSg|title=Akala \u2013 Fire in the Booth Part 2|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Daley released a two-part mixtape, ''Knowledge Is Power'', containing \"Fire in the Booth\", and followed the release with a promotional tour in the autumn of 2012.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In March 2013, Daley announced via his social media feeds that his fourth album would released in May 2013, pushing back the future EP ''The Ruin of Empires'' to later in 2013.{[citation needed}} His fourth album, ''[[The Thieves Banquet]]'', was released on 27 May 2013, including the songs \"Malcolm Said It\", \"Maangamizi\" and \"Lose Myself\" (feat. Josh Osho).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ali |first1=Syed Hamad |title=English rapper Akala unplugged |url=https://gulfnews.com/general/english-rapper-akala-unplugged-1.1233081 |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\n[[File:Akala Blissfields 2015.jpg|thumb|Akala performing at [[Blissfields]] 2015.]]\nIn 2007, Daley was the first hip hop artist to perform his own headline concert in [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/newsnight/review/8073575.stm|publisher=BBC|title=Akala|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> He has performed at various U.K. festivals, including [[V Festival]], [[Wireless]], [[Glastonbury]], [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]], [[The Parklife Weekender|Parklife]], [[Secret Garden Party]] and [[Isle of Wight]], and has supported artists such as [[Christina Aguilera]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview:Akala |url=https://www.thenationalstudent.com/Music/2008-09-10/Interview_Akala.html |website=The National Student |publisher=BigChoiceGroup Ltd. |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[M.I.A. (artist)|MIA]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=DBarry |title=Top British rapper Akala performs workshops on Darling Downs |url=https://www.dailymercury.com.au/news/rappers-on-tour/2869170/ |website=Daily Mercury |publisher=NewsCorp, The Mackay Printing and Publishing Company Pty Ltd |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Richard Ashcroft]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Ashcroft Online : Biography |url=https://www.richardashcroftonline.com/bio.html |website=www.richardashcroftonline.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[Audiobullys]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Audio Bullys + Akala (De Zwerver) |url=https://www.out.be/fr/evenements/88290/audio-bullys-akala/ |website=Out.be |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=fr}}</ref> [[DJ Shadow]],<ref>{{cite web |title=DJ Shadow + Akala + Stateless @ Brixton Academy, London {{!}} Live Music Reviews |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/live/dj-shadow-akala-stateless-brixton-academy-london |website=musicOMH |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 December 2006}}</ref> [[The Gotan Project]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gotan Project @ Brixton Academy, London {{!}} Live Music Reviews |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/live/gotan-project-brixton-academy-london |website=musicOMH |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=3 November 2006}}</ref> and [[Scratch Perverts]] on their U.K/European tours<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pistols |first1=Dub |title=Award winning hip hop artist Akala joins Dub Pistols in the studio |url=http://dubpistolsmusic.co.uk/award-winning-hip-hop-artist-akala-joins-dub-pistols-in-the-studio/ |website=Dub Pistols |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2008, Daley featured at the [[South by Southwest]] music festival in [[Texas]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Savlov |first1=Marc |title=How the West Was Won |url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-02-22/594838/ |website=www.austinchronicle.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> and in 2010 he toured the UK with [[Nas]] and [[Damian Marley]] on the \"Distant Relatives\" tour, which included the British rapper [[Ty (rapper)|Ty]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=News |first1=Janice aka Miss Mad |title=UK MUSIC NEWS: TY AND AKALA OFFICIAL SUPPORT ACTS FOR NAS AND DAMIEN MARLEY \u2018DISTANT RELATIVES\u2019 UK TOUR |url=https://madnewsuk.com/2010/05/31/uk-music-news-ty-and-akala-official-support-acts-for-nas-and-damien-marley-distant-relatives-uk-tour/ |website=MAD NEWS UK |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Daley embarked on his own headline tour of the UK, with 20 dates overall.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pledger |first1=Paul |title=UK grime rapper Akala announces an XXL live tour for November 2010 and new album |url=https://www.allgigs.co.uk/view/article/3013/UK_Grime_Rapper_Akala_Announces_An_XXL_Live_Tour_For_November_2010_And_New_Album.html |website=Allgigs |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was present at the \"One Love:No Borders Hip Hop\" event held in [[Birmingham]], England in April 2011, with Iron Braydz from London, [[Lowkey]], Logic and other up-and-coming UK artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=March 30, 2011 |url=https://dailyurbannews.wordpress.com/2011/03/30/ |website=Daily Urban Newz |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In August 2012, he performed at the [[Outlook Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Outlook Festival 2012 |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/live/outlook-festival-2012-0 |website=Clash Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and in November 2012, he performed at the second edition of NH7 Weekender music festival in Pune, [[India]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Singh |first1=Nirmika |title=Rapper Akala combines Shakespearean verses and sonnets |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/rapper-akala-combines-shakespearean-verses-and-sonnets/story-gjtPlXlRE2EGW4SOop3bqL.html |website=Hindustan Times |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\n\n===Natives===\nIn May 2018, Daley published ''Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire''. The book is part biography, and part polemic on race and class. The overall ideological framework of the book is a pragmatic, socialist-oriented Pan-Africanism that seeks the liberation of all humanity from oppression and exploitation. At the same time, it highlights the shared problems faced by African communities worldwide in a global system of imperialism.<ref>https://www.invent-the-future.org/2018/05/book-review-akala-natives/</ref>\n\nDaley takes his escape from poverty not as proof of personal exceptionalism but of the vagaries and chaotic injustice of race, class and privilege. There is no blindness to the fact that a different fall of the dice might have led to a radically different outcome.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/may/24/natives-race-class-ruins-empire-akala-review</ref> Daley asserts that Britain is not a meritocracy where the barriers of race and class can be simply overcome through hard work and perseverance. He explains his success as the absurd and unexpected consequence of an unequal system that allows the rise of a few while leaving behind the many, no matter how brilliant they are. He points out several times that some of his friends could have been academics or scientists if the obstacles of structural racism and class oppression had not been there.<ref>http://socialistreview.org.uk/438/natives</ref>\n\nOne important idea that emerges from Natives is that, in spite of Britain's record of violence, slavery, genocide and colonialism, there is nonetheless a longstanding progressive trend that is \u201crooted in ideas of freedom, equality and democracy\u201d.<ref>https://www.invent-the-future.org/2018/05/book-review-akala-natives/</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nIn June 2016, Akala supported [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] after mass resignations from his cabinet and a [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|leadership challenge]]. He [[Twitter|tweeted]]: \"The way these dickhead Labor MP's are snaking @jeremycorbyn eediat ting.\"<ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/akalamusic/status/748236119326744576|title=The way these dickhead Labor MP's are snaking @jeremycorbyn eediat ting.|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=29 June 2016|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, he endorsed Corbyn in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]]. He wrote in ''[[The Guardian]]'': \"So why will I be voting now? Jeremy Corbyn. It's not that I am na\u00efve enough to believe that one man (who is, of course, powerless without the people that support him) can fundamentally alter the nature of British politics, or that I think that if Labour wins that the UK will suddenly reflect his personal political convictions, or even that I believe that the prime minister actually runs the country. However for the first time in my adult life, and perhaps for the first time in British history, someone I would consider to be a fundamentally decent human being has a chance of being elected.\"<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/may/12/never-voted-before-jeremy-corbyn-changed-mind|title=By choice, I've never voted before. But Jeremy Corbyn has changed my mind|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, along with 34 other musicians, Akala signed a letter endorsing the Corbyn in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 UK general election]] with a call to end austerity.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/musicians-backing-jeremy-corbyns-labour|title=Musicians backing Jeremy Corbyn\u2019s Labour|work=[[The Guardian]]|location= |publisher= |date=25 November 2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Gayle|first=Damien|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/musicians-backing-jeremy-corbyns-labour|title=Stormzy backs Labour in election with call to end austerity|work=[[The Guardian]]|location= |date=25 November 2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Lectures and speeches==\nDaley has given guest lectures at East 15 Acting School, [[University of Essex]], [[Manchester Metropolitan University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bringing hip hop to the lecture theatre|url=http://www.mmu.ac.uk/news/news-items/1704/|publisher=[[Manchester Metropolitan University]]|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=26 November 2012}}</ref> [[Sydney University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Akala and Artists in conversation|url=http://sydney.edu.au/sydney_ideas/lectures/2016/akala_and_artists_in_conversation.shtml|publisher=[[Sydney University]]|accessdate=6 December 2016|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> [[Sheffield Hallam University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=From hip-hop theatre to lecture theatre|url=http://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/hip-hop-theatre-lecture-theatre?filter=Society|publisher=[[Sheffield Hallam University]]|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=20 November 2013}}</ref> [[Cardiff University]], and the [[International Slavery Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Slavery Remembrance Day 2016 talk|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/srd|publisher=[[National Museums Liverpool]]|accessdate=25 August 2016|date=23 August 2016}}</ref> as well as a workshop on songwriting at the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SOAS Writing Week|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/writing-week/?showprevious=1|publisher=[[School of Oriental and African Studies]]|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He has also spoken at the [[Oxford Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Akala, Full Address and Q&A, Oxford Union|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WUtAxUQjwB4|publisher=[[Oxford Union]] official YouTube channel|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He has also been involved in campaigns to \"decolonise\" the curriculum including giving a talk at the [[University of Leicester]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Decolonising Our Curriculum With AKALA {{!}} Leicester Info |url=https://interests.me/org/leicester-info/story/54274 |website=interests.me |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Advice to peers===\nWhen speaking to schoolchildren or prisoners, or writing lyrics, Daley's message is always to work twice as hard. \u201cMy analysis of institutionalised racism is not \u2018oh, this is an excuse to fail\u2019 \u2013 quite the opposite. The earlier you're aware of the hurdles, the easier they are to jump over.\u201d<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees==\nAkala has received honorary degrees from [[Oxford Brookes]] and [[Brighton University|Brighton]] universities.<ref>https://www.johnmurraypress.co.uk/contributor/akala/</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhoveindependent.co.uk/news/education/albion-boss-to-receive-honorary-doctorate-from-brighton-university-1-8582484|title=Albion boss to receive honorary doctorate from Brighton University|last=Bastable|first=Bex|date=27 July 2018|work=Brighton & Hove Independent|access-date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Album Information\n|-\n|''[[It's Not a Rumour]]''\n*Released: 1 May 2006\n*Singles: \"Roll Wid Us\" \"Bullshit\" \"The Edge\" \"Shakespeare\"\n|-\n|''[[Freedom Lasso]]''\n*Released: 1 October 2007\n*Singles: \"Bit By Bit\" \"Freedom Lasso\" \"Electro Livin\" \"Comedy Tragedy History\"\n|-\n|''[[DoubleThink]]''\n*Released: 3 May 2010\n*Singles: \"XXL\" \"Yours and My Children\" \"Find No Enemy\"\n|-\n|''[[The Thieves Banquet]]''\n*Released: 27 May 2013\n*Singles: \"Lose Myself\" \"Malcolm Said It\"\n|-\n|''Knowledge Is Power II''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/knowledge-is-power-vol.-2/id976529734|title=Knowledge Is Power, Vol. 2|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 30 March 2015\n*Singles: \"Mr. Fire in the Booth\" \"Murder Runs the Globe\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===Compilation===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Album Information\n|-\n|''10 Years of Akala''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/10-years-of-akala/id1145849012|title=10 Years of Akala|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 23 September 2016\n*Singles: \"Giants\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===EPs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!EP Information\n|-\n|''Acoustic Remixes - EP''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/acoustic-remixes-ep/id665940565|title=Acoustic Remixes - EP|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 13 October 2008\n|-\n|''Visions - EP''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/visions-ep/id1261771774|title=Visions - EP|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 28 July 2017\n|-\n|}\n\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Mixtape Information\n|-\n|''The War Mixtape''\n*Released: 1 August 2004\n*Singles: \"Welcome to England\" \"War\"\n|-\n|''A Little Darker'' <small> (with [[Ms. Dynamite]]) </small>\n*Released: 4 September 2006\n|-\n|''The War Mixtape Vol. 2'' \n*Released: 22 September 2008\n|-\n|''Knowledge Is Power Volume 1''  \n*Released: 28 May 2012\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Welcome to England\" (2003)\n* \"War\" (2004)\n* \"Roll Wid Us\" (2005) \u2013 [[UK singles chart|UK]] No. 72<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= [[Guinness World Records Limited]]\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 18}}</ref>\n* \"Bullshit\" (2005)\n* \"The Edge\" (featuring [[Niara Scarlett|Niara]]) (2006)\n* \"Dat Boy Akala\" (featuring Low Deep) (2006)\n* \"Shakespeare\" (2006)\n* \"Doin' Nuffin\" / \"Hold Your Head Up\" (2006)\n* \"Bit By Bit\" (2007)\n* \"Freedom Lasso\" (2007)\n* \"Where I'm From\" (2007)\n* \"Comedy Tragedy History\" (2008)\n* \"XXL\" (2010)\n* \"Yours and My Children\" (2010)\n* \"Find No Enemy\" (2011)\n* \"Lose Myself\" (featuring [[Josh Osho]]) (2013)\n* \"Mr. Fire in the Booth\" (2015)\n* \"Giants\" (featuring Kabaka Pyramid & Marshall) (2016)\n\n==Songs used in other media==\n*The song \"Roll Wid Us\", was used in the 2006 British film ''[[Kidulthood]]''. \n*The song \"The Edge\", from ''It's Not A Rumour'', was used in the ''[[NBA 2K10]] video game.\n*The song \"Shakespeare\" was used on a [[Channel 4]] advert for their ''Street Summer''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n* [http://www.akalamusic.com/ Official website]\n* {{Discogs artist | artist = Akala (2) | name = Akala}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blast BBC Blast]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p023d7hb/p023d6zr \"Akala's visit to Jamaica\"], BBC.\n* ''[https://ia801501.us.archive.org/5/items/NativesRaceAndClassInTheRuinsOfEmpireByAkala/Natives_%20Race%20and%20Class%20in%20the%20Ruins%20of%20Empire%20by%20Akala.pdf Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire]'' PDF\n* ''[https://archive.org/download/NativesRaceAndClassInTheRuinsOfEmpireByAkala/Natives_%20Race%20and%20Class%20in%20the%20Ruins%20of%20Empire%20by%20Akala.epub Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire''] EPUB\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akala}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-racism activists]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:Black British musicians]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:People from Kentish Town]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Akala\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Akala crop 2014.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Akala in 2014\n| birth_name       = Kingslee James McLean Daley\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1983|12|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]], England\n| origin           = [[Kentish Town]], [[London]], England\n| death_date       = \n| genre            = [[British hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], poet, journalist, songwriter and activist\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present\n| label            = Immovable Ltd (Illa State Records)\n| associated_acts  = [[Lowkey]]<br>[[Ms. Dynamite]]<br/>[[Durrty Goodz]]<br/>[[Black the Ripper]]\n| website          = {{url|http://akalamusic.com}}\n}}\n'''Kingslee James McLean Daley''' (born 1 December 1983), better known by the stage name '''Akala''', is an British rapper, journalist, author, activist and poet.\n\nHe is originally from [[Kentish Town]], north [[London]]. In 2006, he was voted the Best Hip Hop Act at the [[Music of Black Origin Awards|MOBO Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/akala-mn0000560354/biography|title=Akala|author=Chris True|work=AllMusic}}</ref> and has been included on the annual ''[[Powerlist]]'' of the 100 most influential Black British people in the UK. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mills |first1=Kelly-Ann |title=Raheem Sterling joins Meghan and Stormzy in top 100 most influential black Brits |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/black-powerlist-2020-raheem-sterling-20721033 |website=mirror |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDaley was born in [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]], in 1983 to a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother and [[Jamaica]]n father who separated before he was born and grew up with his mother \"in the cliched, single-parent working-class family,\"<ref>Daley quote from his book Natives.</ref> in [[Kentish Town]], north London.<ref>Kate Mossman, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/02/akala-thieves-banquet-rap-interview \"Akala: Dynamite by any other name\u2026\"], ''[[The Observer]]'', 2 June 2013.</ref><ref>Brian Rose, [https://londonrealacademy.com/fight-the-power-akala-and-the-power-of-the-word/ \"Fight the Power \u2014 Akala and the Power of the Word\"], London Real Academy, 20 October 2015.</ref> He remembers the day he realised that his mum was white,<ref>http://socialistreview.org.uk/438/natives</ref> and was embarrassed by her whiteness, and that she could \u201cnever really \u2018get it\u2019\u201d when it came to racism.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/akala-s-race-polemic-up-for-oldest-literary-prize-6xl7vq6f8</ref> Daley's older sister is rapper [[Ms. Dynamite]].\n\nHis stepdad was a stage manager at the [[Hackney Empire]] theatre, and he often visited it before his teens.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> He also attended pan-African Saturday school, stating \"I benefited massively from a specifically black community-led self-education tradition that we don\u2019t talk about very much because it doesn\u2019t fit with the image [of black families]\".<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> When accepting honorary degrees, he has said he \"would like to thank the entire Caribbean pan-African community that helped me through school and encouraged an intellectual curiosity and self development from a very young age.\"<ref>https://archive.voice-online.co.uk/article/akala-receives-honorary-doctorate</ref> \n\nAt age 6, Daley's state primary school put him in a special needs group for pupils with learning difficulties and English as a second language.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> Daley saw a friend attacked by a meat cleaver to the skull when he was 12, and carried a knife himself for a period<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> He went on to achieve ten [[GCSEs|GCSE]] and took maths a year early. He has said he \"was in the top 1 per cent of GCSEs in the country. [He] got 100 per cent in [his] English exam.\"<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref> As a teenager, Daley focused on football, being on the schoolboy books of both [[West Ham United]] and [[AFC Wimbledon]], and dropped out of college.<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/Akala/+wiki</ref> Daley did not attend university, but has said he often envies those who do.<ref>\"He told graduates: \u201cI can\u2019t lie, I often envy those of you who do get to go, people like you \u2026 who are about to remake the world, or at least this country. That\u2019s how serious these four years are. What will you do with the time you spent here and the education you have been privileged to be loaned by the rest of society?\u201d https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2018/07-31-akala-urges-graduates-develop-good-habits.aspx</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n===2003\u201309: Early years and breakthrough===\n[[File:Melodee and Akala.jpg|thumb|left|Akala (right) in 2009.]]\nDaley got his stage name from [[Acala]], a [[Buddhist]] term for \"immovable\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesituation.co.uk/ukartists/06/akala/akala.html |title=Akala interview on \"The Situation\" website |accessdate=21 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912013648/http://www.thesituation.co.uk/ukartists/06/akala/akala.html |archivedate=12 September 2012 }}</ref> and started releasing music in 2003 from his own independent music label, Illa State Records. He released his first mixtape,''The War Mixtape'', in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala (2) - The War Mixtape |url=https://www.discogs.com/Akala-The-War-Mixtape/release/1305358 |website=Discogs |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he released his first album, ''[[It's Not a Rumour]]''. This proved to be his breakthrough album, containing the single \"Shakespeare\" (a reference to his self-proclaimed title \"The Black Shakespeare\") which made the [[BBC Radio 1]] playlist.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Webb |first1=Adam |title=BBC - Music - Review of Akala - It's Not a Rumour |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/ddvr/ |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> His work was recognised with the [[Music of Black Origin Awards|MOBO Award]] for Best Hip Hop Act.<ref>{{cite web |title=MOBO Awards 2006 {{!}} MOBO Organisation |url=https://www.mobo.com/history/2006 |website=www.mobo.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally in 2006, a mixtape, ''A Little Darker'', was released under the name \"Illa State\", featuring Akala and his sister, [[Ms. Dynamite]], as well as cameo appearances by many other artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala (2) & Ms. Dynamite - A Little Darker EP |url=https://www.discogs.com/Akala-2-Ms-Dynamite-A-Little-Darker-EP/release/709575 |website=Discogs |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDaley appeared for a live session on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] where he was challenged to come up with a rap containing as many Shakespeare play titles as he could manage, he wrote and performed a minute-long rap containing 27 different Shakespeare play titles in under half an hour and later recorded these lyrics in the studio and turned it into the single \"Comedy Tragedy History\".<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Two - Shakespeare Live! From the RSC - Akala |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/2vCgZCVB5gPpNYCXCTWs1JS/akala |website=BBC |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Daley released his second album, ''[[Freedom Lasso]]'', containing the \"Comedy Tragedy History\" track. The song \"Love in my Eyes\" heavily sampled  [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]]' song \"[[Mittageisen|Love in a void]]\" with the voice of [[Siouxsie Sioux]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macpherson |first1=Alex |title=CD: Akala, Freedom Lasso |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/sep/28/urban.shopping |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=27 September 2007}}</ref> In 2008, ''The War Mixtape Vol. 2'' was released, along with an EP of acoustic remixes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala Releases His Long Awaited Mixtape Entitled The War Mixtape Vol 2 |url=https://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=42842 |website=Top40-Charts.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present: ''Doublethink'', ''Knowledge Is Power'', and beyond===\n[[File:Akala Hull Jazz Festival 2015.jpg|thumb|Akala at the [[Hull Jazz Festival]] 2015.]]\nDaley's third studio album, ''[[DoubleThink]]'', was released in 2010, and holds a strong theme of [[George Orwell]]'s popular novel ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Akala: Doublethink Interview (video) |url=https://www.orwellfoundation.com/the-orwell-foundation/orwell/library/akala-doublethink-interview-video/ |website=The Orwell Foundation |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> ''DoubleThink'' contains tracks such as \"Find No Enemy\" and \"Yours and My Children\" detailing some of the sights he saw on his trip to Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andrews |first1=Charlotte Richardson |title=Brit-hop: 10 of the best |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/jul/09/brit-hop-10-of-the-best |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=9 July 2014}}</ref> In November 2010, Daley headlined a live performance at the [[British Library]], to launch the \"Evolving English\" exhibition and featured performances by British poet [[Zena Edwards]], comedian [[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]] and British rapper [[Lowkey]] which also included Daley taking part in a hip hop panel discussion alongside [[Saul Williams]], U.S professor [[MK Asante]] and Lowkey.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Love |first1=Emma |title=Hip-hop deciphered at the British Library |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/hip-hop-deciphered-at-the-british-library-2143735.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=26 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Evolving English One Language Many Voices80 |url=https://www.bl.uk/press-releases/2010/november/evolving-english-one-language-many-voices80 |website=The British Library |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Daley appeared on [[Charlie Sloth]]'s show on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|Radio 1Xtra]] on 18 July 2011, performing \"Fire in the Booth\", and after the great reception it received he returned again in May 2012 and provided \"Part 2\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJOp1CqzaSg|title=Akala \u2013 Fire in the Booth Part 2|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Daley released a two-part mixtape, ''Knowledge Is Power'', containing \"Fire in the Booth\", and followed the release with a promotional tour in the autumn of 2012.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In March 2013, Daley announced via his social media feeds that his fourth album would released in May 2013, pushing back the future EP ''The Ruin of Empires'' to later in 2013.{[citation needed}} His fourth album, ''[[The Thieves Banquet]]'', was released on 27 May 2013, including the songs \"Malcolm Said It\", \"Maangamizi\" and \"Lose Myself\" (feat. Josh Osho).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ali |first1=Syed Hamad |title=English rapper Akala unplugged |url=https://gulfnews.com/general/english-rapper-akala-unplugged-1.1233081 |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\n[[File:Akala Blissfields 2015.jpg|thumb|Akala performing at [[Blissfields]] 2015.]]\nIn 2007, Daley was the first hip hop artist to perform his own headline concert in [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/newsnight/review/8073575.stm|publisher=BBC|title=Akala|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> He has performed at various U.K. festivals, including [[V Festival]], [[Wireless]], [[Glastonbury]], [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]], [[The Parklife Weekender|Parklife]], [[Secret Garden Party]] and [[Isle of Wight]], and has supported artists such as [[Christina Aguilera]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview:Akala |url=https://www.thenationalstudent.com/Music/2008-09-10/Interview_Akala.html |website=The National Student |publisher=BigChoiceGroup Ltd. |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[M.I.A. (artist)|MIA]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=DBarry |title=Top British rapper Akala performs workshops on Darling Downs |url=https://www.dailymercury.com.au/news/rappers-on-tour/2869170/ |website=Daily Mercury |publisher=NewsCorp, The Mackay Printing and Publishing Company Pty Ltd |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Richard Ashcroft]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Ashcroft Online : Biography |url=https://www.richardashcroftonline.com/bio.html |website=www.richardashcroftonline.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[Audiobullys]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Audio Bullys + Akala (De Zwerver) |url=https://www.out.be/fr/evenements/88290/audio-bullys-akala/ |website=Out.be |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=fr}}</ref> [[DJ Shadow]],<ref>{{cite web |title=DJ Shadow + Akala + Stateless @ Brixton Academy, London {{!}} Live Music Reviews |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/live/dj-shadow-akala-stateless-brixton-academy-london |website=musicOMH |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 December 2006}}</ref> [[The Gotan Project]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gotan Project @ Brixton Academy, London {{!}} Live Music Reviews |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/live/gotan-project-brixton-academy-london |website=musicOMH |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=3 November 2006}}</ref> and [[Scratch Perverts]] on their U.K/European tours<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pistols |first1=Dub |title=Award winning hip hop artist Akala joins Dub Pistols in the studio |url=http://dubpistolsmusic.co.uk/award-winning-hip-hop-artist-akala-joins-dub-pistols-in-the-studio/ |website=Dub Pistols |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2008, Daley featured at the [[South by Southwest]] music festival in [[Texas]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Savlov |first1=Marc |title=How the West Was Won |url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-02-22/594838/ |website=www.austinchronicle.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> and in 2010 he toured the UK with [[Nas]] and [[Damian Marley]] on the \"Distant Relatives\" tour, which included the British rapper [[Ty (rapper)|Ty]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=News |first1=Janice aka Miss Mad |title=UK MUSIC NEWS: TY AND AKALA OFFICIAL SUPPORT ACTS FOR NAS AND DAMIEN MARLEY \u2018DISTANT RELATIVES\u2019 UK TOUR |url=https://madnewsuk.com/2010/05/31/uk-music-news-ty-and-akala-official-support-acts-for-nas-and-damien-marley-distant-relatives-uk-tour/ |website=MAD NEWS UK |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Daley embarked on his own headline tour of the UK, with 20 dates overall.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pledger |first1=Paul |title=UK grime rapper Akala announces an XXL live tour for November 2010 and new album |url=https://www.allgigs.co.uk/view/article/3013/UK_Grime_Rapper_Akala_Announces_An_XXL_Live_Tour_For_November_2010_And_New_Album.html |website=Allgigs |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was present at the \"One Love:No Borders Hip Hop\" event held in [[Birmingham]], England in April 2011, with Iron Braydz from London, [[Lowkey]], Logic and other up-and-coming UK artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=March 30, 2011 |url=https://dailyurbannews.wordpress.com/2011/03/30/ |website=Daily Urban Newz |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In August 2012, he performed at the [[Outlook Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Outlook Festival 2012 |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/live/outlook-festival-2012-0 |website=Clash Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and in November 2012, he performed at the second edition of NH7 Weekender music festival in Pune, [[India]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Singh |first1=Nirmika |title=Rapper Akala combines Shakespearean verses and sonnets |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/rapper-akala-combines-shakespearean-verses-and-sonnets/story-gjtPlXlRE2EGW4SOop3bqL.html |website=Hindustan Times |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\n\n===Natives===\nIn May 2018, Daley published ''Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire''. The book is part biography, and part polemic on race and class. The overall ideological framework of the book is a pragmatic, socialist-oriented Pan-Africanism that seeks the liberation of all humanity from oppression and exploitation. At the same time, it highlights the shared problems faced by African communities worldwide in a global system of imperialism.<ref>https://www.invent-the-future.org/2018/05/book-review-akala-natives/</ref>\n\nDaley takes his escape from poverty not as proof of personal exceptionalism but of the vagaries and chaotic injustice of race, class and privilege. There is no blindness to the fact that a different fall of the dice might have led to a radically different outcome.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/may/24/natives-race-class-ruins-empire-akala-review</ref> Daley asserts that Britain is not a meritocracy where the barriers of race and class can be simply overcome through hard work and perseverance. He explains his success as the absurd and unexpected consequence of an unequal system that allows the rise of a few while leaving behind the many, no matter how brilliant they are. He points out several times that some of his friends could have been academics or scientists if the obstacles of structural racism and class oppression had not been there.<ref>http://socialistreview.org.uk/438/natives</ref>\n\nOne important idea that emerges from Natives is that, in spite of Britain's record of violence, slavery, genocide and colonialism, there is nonetheless a longstanding progressive trend that is \u201crooted in ideas of freedom, equality and democracy\u201d.<ref>https://www.invent-the-future.org/2018/05/book-review-akala-natives/</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nIn June 2016, Akala supported [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] after mass resignations from his cabinet and a [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|leadership challenge]]. He [[Twitter|tweeted]]: \"The way these dickhead Labor MP's are snaking @jeremycorbyn eediat ting.\"<ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/akalamusic/status/748236119326744576|title=The way these dickhead Labor MP's are snaking @jeremycorbyn eediat ting.|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=29 June 2016|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, he endorsed Corbyn in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]]. He wrote in ''[[The Guardian]]'': \"So why will I be voting now? Jeremy Corbyn. It's not that I am na\u00efve enough to believe that one man (who is, of course, powerless without the people that support him) can fundamentally alter the nature of British politics, or that I think that if Labour wins that the UK will suddenly reflect his personal political convictions, or even that I believe that the prime minister actually runs the country. However for the first time in my adult life, and perhaps for the first time in British history, someone I would consider to be a fundamentally decent human being has a chance of being elected.\"<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/may/12/never-voted-before-jeremy-corbyn-changed-mind|title=By choice, I've never voted before. But Jeremy Corbyn has changed my mind|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, along with 34 other musicians, Akala signed a letter endorsing the Corbyn in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 UK general election]] with a call to end austerity.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/musicians-backing-jeremy-corbyns-labour|title=Musicians backing Jeremy Corbyn\u2019s Labour|work=[[The Guardian]]|location= |publisher= |date=25 November 2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Gayle|first=Damien|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/musicians-backing-jeremy-corbyns-labour|title=Stormzy backs Labour in election with call to end austerity|work=[[The Guardian]]|location= |date=25 November 2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Lectures and speeches==\nDaley has given guest lectures at East 15 Acting School, [[University of Essex]], [[Manchester Metropolitan University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bringing hip hop to the lecture theatre|url=http://www.mmu.ac.uk/news/news-items/1704/|publisher=[[Manchester Metropolitan University]]|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=26 November 2012}}</ref> [[Sydney University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Akala and Artists in conversation|url=http://sydney.edu.au/sydney_ideas/lectures/2016/akala_and_artists_in_conversation.shtml|publisher=[[Sydney University]]|accessdate=6 December 2016|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> [[Sheffield Hallam University]],<ref>{{cite web|title=From hip-hop theatre to lecture theatre|url=http://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/hip-hop-theatre-lecture-theatre?filter=Society|publisher=[[Sheffield Hallam University]]|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=20 November 2013}}</ref> [[Cardiff University]], and the [[International Slavery Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Slavery Remembrance Day 2016 talk|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/srd|publisher=[[National Museums Liverpool]]|accessdate=25 August 2016|date=23 August 2016}}</ref> as well as a workshop on songwriting at the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SOAS Writing Week|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/writing-week/?showprevious=1|publisher=[[School of Oriental and African Studies]]|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He has also spoken at the [[Oxford Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Akala, Full Address and Q&A, Oxford Union|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WUtAxUQjwB4|publisher=[[Oxford Union]] official YouTube channel|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He has also been involved in campaigns to \"decolonise\" the curriculum including giving a talk at the [[University of Leicester]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Decolonising Our Curriculum With AKALA {{!}} Leicester Info |url=https://interests.me/org/leicester-info/story/54274 |website=interests.me |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Advice to peers===\nWhen speaking to schoolchildren or prisoners, or writing lyrics, Daley's message is always to work twice as hard. \u201cMy analysis of institutionalised racism is not \u2018oh, this is an excuse to fail\u2019 \u2013 quite the opposite. The earlier you're aware of the hurdles, the easier they are to jump over.\u201d<ref>https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/04/akala-i-don-t-enjoy-explaining-black-people-are-human-beings</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees==\nAkala has received honorary degrees from [[Oxford Brookes]] and [[Brighton University|Brighton]] universities.<ref>https://www.johnmurraypress.co.uk/contributor/akala/</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhoveindependent.co.uk/news/education/albion-boss-to-receive-honorary-doctorate-from-brighton-university-1-8582484|title=Albion boss to receive honorary doctorate from Brighton University|last=Bastable|first=Bex|date=27 July 2018|work=Brighton & Hove Independent|access-date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Album Information\n|-\n|''[[It's Not a Rumour]]''\n*Released: 1 May 2006\n*Singles: \"Roll Wid Us\" \"Bullshit\" \"The Edge\" \"Shakespeare\"\n|-\n|''[[Freedom Lasso]]''\n*Released: 1 October 2007\n*Singles: \"Bit By Bit\" \"Freedom Lasso\" \"Electro Livin\" \"Comedy Tragedy History\"\n|-\n|''[[DoubleThink]]''\n*Released: 3 May 2010\n*Singles: \"XXL\" \"Yours and My Children\" \"Find No Enemy\"\n|-\n|''[[The Thieves Banquet]]''\n*Released: 27 May 2013\n*Singles: \"Lose Myself\" \"Malcolm Said It\"\n|-\n|''Knowledge Is Power II''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/knowledge-is-power-vol.-2/id976529734|title=Knowledge Is Power, Vol. 2|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 30 March 2015\n*Singles: \"Mr. Fire in the Booth\" \"Murder Runs the Globe\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===Compilation===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Album Information\n|-\n|''10 Years of Akala''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/10-years-of-akala/id1145849012|title=10 Years of Akala|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 23 September 2016\n*Singles: \"Giants\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===EPs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!EP Information\n|-\n|''Acoustic Remixes - EP''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/acoustic-remixes-ep/id665940565|title=Acoustic Remixes - EP|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 13 October 2008\n|-\n|''Visions - EP''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/visions-ep/id1261771774|title=Visions - EP|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n*Released: 28 July 2017\n|-\n|}\n\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Mixtape Information\n|-\n|''The War Mixtape''\n*Released: 1 August 2004\n*Singles: \"Welcome to England\" \"War\"\n|-\n|''A Little Darker'' <small> (with [[Ms. Dynamite]]) </small>\n*Released: 4 September 2006\n|-\n|''The War Mixtape Vol. 2'' \n*Released: 22 September 2008\n|-\n|''Knowledge Is Power Volume 1''  \n*Released: 28 May 2012\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Welcome to England\" (2003)\n* \"War\" (2004)\n* \"Roll Wid Us\" (2005) \u2013 [[UK singles chart|UK]] No. 72<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= [[Guinness World Records Limited]]\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 18}}</ref>\n* \"Bullshit\" (2005)\n* \"The Edge\" (featuring [[Niara Scarlett|Niara]]) (2006)\n* \"Dat Boy Akala\" (featuring Low Deep) (2006)\n* \"Shakespeare\" (2006)\n* \"Doin' Nuffin\" / \"Hold Your Head Up\" (2006)\n* \"Bit By Bit\" (2007)\n* \"Freedom Lasso\" (2007)\n* \"Where I'm From\" (2007)\n* \"Comedy Tragedy History\" (2008)\n* \"XXL\" (2010)\n* \"Yours and My Children\" (2010)\n* \"Find No Enemy\" (2011)\n* \"Lose Myself\" (featuring [[Josh Osho]]) (2013)\n* \"Mr. Fire in the Booth\" (2015)\n* \"Giants\" (featuring Kabaka Pyramid & Marshall) (2016)\n\n==Songs used in other media==\n*The song \"Roll Wid Us\", was used in the 2006 British film ''[[Kidulthood]]''. \n*The song \"The Edge\", from ''It's Not A Rumour'', was used in the ''[[NBA 2K10]] video game.\n*The song \"Shakespeare\" was used on a [[Channel 4]] advert for their ''Street Summer''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n* [http://www.akalamusic.com/ Official website]\n* {{Discogs artist | artist = Akala (2) | name = Akala}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blast BBC Blast]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p023d7hb/p023d6zr \"Akala's visit to Jamaica\"], BBC.\n* ''[https://ia801501.us.archive.org/5/items/NativesRaceAndClassInTheRuinsOfEmpireByAkala/Natives_%20Race%20and%20Class%20in%20the%20Ruins%20of%20Empire%20by%20Akala.pdf Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire]'' PDF\n* ''[https://archive.org/download/NativesRaceAndClassInTheRuinsOfEmpireByAkala/Natives_%20Race%20and%20Class%20in%20the%20Ruins%20of%20Empire%20by%20Akala.epub Natives: Race and Class in the Ruins of Empire''] EPUB\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akala}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-racism activists]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:Black British musicians]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:People from Kentish Town]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akala_(rapper)"}
{"title_page": "Joji (musician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese musician and web actor}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joji\n| birth_name         = George Kusunoki Miller<ref name=\"ACE Repertory\">{{cite web |title=ACE Repertory \u2013 Joji Kusunoki |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/writer/886198670/KUSUNOKI%20JOJI |website=www.ascap.com |accessdate=14 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330145422/https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/writer/886198670/KUSUNOKI%20JOJI |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| caption            = Joji performing in August 2018\n| image              = Joji Performing Live in 2018 (cropped).png\n| birth_date         = <!-- Do not change the birth date without adding a reliable source -->{{birth date and age|df=no|1992|9|18}}<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\">{{cite web|title=Joji on Apple Music|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/joji/1258279972|website=Apple Music|accessdate=14 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214143719/https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/joji/1258279972|archive-date=14 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Osaka]], Japan<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\" />\n| other_names        = {{flatlist|\n* Filthy Frank\n* Pink Guy\n}}\n| education          = [[Canadian Academy]]<br />[[New York Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* rapper\n* record producer\n}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| origin          = [[Higashinada-ku, Kobe]], Japan<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\" /><ref name=\"Canadian Academy\" />\n| genre           = {{ubl|'''Joji'''|{{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"billboard interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear' |last=Kelley |first=Caitlin |date=7 December 2017 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |archive-date=8 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[trip hop]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\" />\n* [[lo-fi]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\" />}}\n'''Filthy Frank''' / '''Pink Guy'''|{{hlist|[[Surreal comedy]]|[[satire]]|[[comedy hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career-Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear' |last=Kelley |first=Caitlin |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2018 |archivedate=8 June 2018 |url-status=live |quote=\"He won\u2019t rap on a Joji track like he does as Pink Guy&nbsp;...\" & \"Miller has been growing out of the brand of comedy associated with Pink Guy&nbsp;...\"}}</ref>}}\n\n}}\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vocals]]\n* [[ukulele]]\n}}\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[88rising]]\n* [[Doug Morris|12 Tone Music]]\n}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| channel_name = DizastaMusic\n| channel_name2 = TVFilthyFrank\n| channel_name3= TooDamnFilthy\n| years_active = 2008\u20132017\n| subscribers  = 13.1 million (combined)\n| views        = 2.4 billion (combined)\n| network      = ScaleLab<ref name=\"SocialBlade\">{{cite web|title=TVFilthyFrank YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|publisher=socialblade.com|accessdate=29 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816233823/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| silver_button   = yes\n| silver_year     = 2012\n| gold_button     = yes\n| gold_year       = 2015\n| diamond_button  = no\n| ruby_button     = no\n| stats_update    = 27 April 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''George Kusunoki Miller''' (born 18 September 1992<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\" />), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Joji''' and formerly by his online [[Pseudonym|aliases]] '''Filthy Frank''' and '''Pink Guy''', is a Japanese<!-- do NOT add half Japanese, half Australian; ethnicity does not belong in the lead section per [[MOS:BLPLEAD]] --> singer, songwriter, rapper, record producer, author, and former [[Internet celebrity|Internet personality]] and comedian.\n\nMiller's start as an entertainer began on his now defunct [[YouTuber|YouTube channels]], DizastaMusic, TooDamnFilthy, and TVFilthyFrank,<ref name=\"announcement tweet\">{{cite tweet|number=946807308541218816|user=FilthyFrank|title=This is old news but I figured I'd give an official statement. Thank you for your understanding and god bless.|date=29 December 2017|access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> that consisted of rap songs, rants, extreme challenges, [[ukulele]] performances<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsucurrent.nova.edu/soundbite-pink-season-by-pink-guy/|title=Soundbite: \"Pink Season\" by Pink Guy|work=The Current|access-date=14 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730112011/https://nsucurrent.nova.edu/soundbite-pink-season-by-pink-guy/|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and a [[shock humor]] show titled ''The Filthy Frank Show'', with most of the main characters played by Miller, including the titular character of Filthy Frank.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/01/pink-guy-pink-season-filthy-frank-george-miller-interview|title=The Man Behind Pink Guy's Bizarre Chart-Topping Album 'Pink Season'|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|access-date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308080936/https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/01/pink-guy-pink-season-filthy-frank-george-miller-interview|archive-date=8 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\">{{Cite news|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2017/12/joji-quits-pink-guy-filthy-frank-comedy|title=Joji Explains Decision to Quit Filthy Frank and Pink Guy as He Pursues Music Career|work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=29 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229223130/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2017/12/joji-quits-pink-guy-filthy-frank-comedy|archive-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> To complement his TVFilthyFrank channel, Miller produced [[comedy hip hop]] music under his Pink Guy alias, who is also a [[zentai]]-wearing recurring character on ''The Filthy Frank Show'', with his songs featured on the show and his discography spanning two full-length projects and an extended play. Miller's videos had widespread impact, including starting a viral dance craze known as the [[Harlem Shake (meme)|Harlem Shake]], which was directly responsible for the debut of [[Baauer]]'s \"[[Harlem Shake (song)|Harlem Shake]]\" song [[List of songs that debuted number one on the Billboard Hot 100|atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|title=Straight outta... China? The young Asian artists bucking hip-hop trends|first=Marian|last=Liu|work=CNN|access-date=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331104359/https://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|archive-date=31 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"mashable\">{{Cite news|url=https://mashable.com/2013/02/12/youtube-harlem-shake/#r8YJ3.GUFZqb|title=YouTube: Here's How 'Harlem Shake' Went Viral|last=Taylor|first=Chris|work=Mashable|access-date=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428154325/https://mashable.com/2013/02/12/youtube-harlem-shake/#r8YJ3.GUFZqb|archive-date=28 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Many YouTube personalities have made major or [[cameo appearance|cameo]] appearances on ''The Filthy Frank Show'', including [[h3h3Productions]], [[iDubbbz]], [[JonTron]], [[Michael Stevens (educator)|Michael Stevens]], and [[PewDiePie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wldE_4xjVQ|title=IT'S JUST A PRANK BRO|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=December 11, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225513/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wldE_4xjVQ|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Vuw-burI0|title=HUMAN CAKE|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=August 3, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225511/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Vuw-burI0|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6bQibFNs2E|title=A WAR IS COMING...|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=July 21, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6bQibFNs2E|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Miller stated he had retired the channel to focus on his music career, under the name Joji, producing more nuanced and serious music, releasing the EP ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'', which peaked at number 58 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and his debut studio album ''[[Ballads 1]]'', which reached number 1 on [[Billboard R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart|''Billboard''{{'}}s top R&B and hip-hop chart]] in November 2018. With this, Miller became the first Asian-born artist to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/joji-makes-history-on-billboard-chart/|title=Joji Becomes First Asian Artist to Top Billboard R&B/Hip-Hop Album Chart|work=Highsnobiety|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018|first=Renz|last=Ofiaza}}</ref> Miller's music has been described as a mix between [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[lo-fi]] and [[trip hop]].\n\n== Early life ==\nGeorge Kusunoki Miller<ref name=\"ACE Repertory\" /> was born on 18 September 1992,<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\" /> in [[Osaka]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\">{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-for-New-Single-Will-He-Announces-New-EP-20171018|title=Joji Shares Video for New Single 'Will He'; Announces New EP|publisher=BroadwayWorld|date=18 October 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107012813/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-for-New-Single-Will-He-Announces-New-EP-20171018|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He attended an international school, [[Canadian Academy]], in [[Kobe]], Japan, where he graduated in 2012.<ref name=\"Canadian Academy\">{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/canadian.academy/docs/ca_review_fall_2012/7|title=CA Review Fall 2012|publisher=Canadian Academy|pages=4\u20135|access-date=16 January 2017|via=Issuu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927043055/https://issuu.com/canadian.academy/docs/ca_review_fall_2012/7|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At age 18, he left Japan and traveled to the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=VIz05lZMKyM|title=Joji Goes Desk Shopping, \"Phones\" Drake & Performs with 88rising|author=HYPEBEAST|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018|time=1:10|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> He was enrolled at New York Institute of Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyit.edu/files/special_events/Events_SOURCE_ProgramAbstracts_2016.pdf|title=Source: Symposium of University Research and Creative Expression|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2016|website=New York Institute of Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is half [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and half [[Australians|Australian]].<ref name=\"FrankExposed\">{{Citation|last=DizastaMusic|title=Filthy Frank Exposes Himself?|date=5 July 2017|url=https://archive.org/details/FILTHYFRANKEXPOSESHIMSELF_201707|access-date=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nMiller made attempts to maintain his privacy, such as deleting the video \"Filthy Frank Exposes Himself?\", where he revealed himself to be a college student in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and that he did not want to reveal personal information for fear of not being able to get a job later on due to the nature of his show.<ref name=\"FrankExposed\" />\n\n== Entertainment career ==\n=== ''The Filthy Frank Show'' (2011\u20132017) ===\nMiller created the Filthy Frank character during his time on his DizastaMusic [[YouTube]] channel, on which he created sketch comedy-based content. The channel started gaining popularity once he conceptualised Filthy Frank, a character who is described as the anti-vlogger of YouTube, in September 2015.<ref>{{Cite AV media|date=6 September 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6UYz2eNoS8&t=6m39s|title=TND Podcast #17 ft. George Miller a.k.a. Filthy Frank|time=6:39|publisher=The Needle Drop|access-date=22 January 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204014745/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6UYz2eNoS8&t=6m39s|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The first known video on this particular channel (before his creation of the Frank character) was uploaded on 19 June 2008, and was titled \"Lil Jon falls off a table\".<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=hB_LvjoAF2Q|title=Lil Jon falls off a table|date=19 June 2008|publisher=George Miller|access-date=30 June 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225124242/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hB_LvjoAF2Q|archive-date=25 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The DizastaMusic channel has over 915,000 subscribers and is nearing 170 million views {{As of|2019|9|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/DizastaMusic/about|title=DizastaMusic \u2013 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=30 June 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517212153/https://www.youtube.com/user/DizastaMusic/about|archive-date=17 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 August 2014, Miller uploaded a video to the DizastaMusic channel, announcing that he would not be posting any more video content onto the channel, under the risk of losing the channel due to the numerous copyright and community strikes it received.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=New Channel: TVFilthyFrank|date=15 August 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qSfcvIA366A|publisher=George Miller|access-date=26 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623131329/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qSfcvIA366A|archive-date=23 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn Miller's channel, TVFilthyFrank, he had many different series on his channel, such as \"Food\" (\u548c\u98df\u30e9\u30c3\u30d7), \"Japanese 101\", \"Wild Games\" and \"Loser Reads Hater Comments\". This channel currently has a total of 7.01 million subscribers and 1.02 billion views {{As of|2020|1|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/user/TVFilthyFrank/about|title=TVFilthyFrank \u2014 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=9 February 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808222325/https://m.youtube.com/user/TVFilthyFrank/about|archive-date=8 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|title=TVFilthyFrank YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics|publisher=Socialblade.com|access-date=9 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816233823/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller opened a third channel, TooDamnFilthy, on 1 July 2014.<ref name=\"TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/about|title=TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=16 March 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406160233/https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/about|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On this channel he had two series, \"Japanese 101\", which is also featured on his main channel, and \"Cringe of the Week\", which is usually abbreviated to \"COTW\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/playlists|title=TooDamnFilthy \u2013 Playlists|publisher=George Miller|access-date=13 October 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> {{As of|2019|9}}, TooDamnFilthy has 2.1 million subscribers and 258 million views.<ref name=\"TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About\" />\n\nOn 27 September 2017, Miller announced the release of his first and currently only book, titled ''Francis of the Filth'', which addresses things uncovered in ''The Filthy Frank Show'', and serves as a culmination of the series.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUrwgtQpjY8 |title=Francis Of The Filth (Out Now) |date=27 September 2017 |access-date=27 September 2017 |publisher=George Miller |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927230158/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUrwgtQpjY8 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2017, Miller released a statement on Twitter explaining that he had stopped producing comedy, including Filthy Frank, due to both \"serious health conditions\" and his personal lack of interest in continuing the series.<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|work=Billboard|access-date=29 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2018, Miller stated in a BBC Radio 1 interview that he had no choice but to stop producing comedy due to his health condition.<ref>{{Citation|last=Jambino|title=Joji Interview \u2013 BBC Radio 1 (Annie Mac)|date=2018-09-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BE34LTLrqoA|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Legacy ====\nMiller's Filthy Frank show has had a profound impact on internet culture, responsible for creating many [[internet memes]].<ref name=\"Diamondback\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dbknews.com/2016/12/02/filthy-frank-youtube-george-miller/|title=Filthy Frank and the inexplicable, weird, kind of gross side of Youtube|work=[[The Diamondback]]|date=December 1, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2018|first=Samuel|last=Atenza|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025613/http://www.dbknews.com/2016/12/02/filthy-frank-youtube-george-miller/|archive-date=8 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller's show has been hailed as \"the epitome of odd\".<ref name=\"Diamondback\" />\n\nMiller's videos had widespread impact, which included starting a viral dance craze known as the [[Harlem Shake (meme)|Harlem Shake]] back in 2013, which was directly responsible for the debut of [[Baauer]]'s \"[[Harlem Shake (song)|Harlem Shake]]\" song [[List of songs that debuted number one on the Billboard Hot 100|atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"cnn\" /><ref name=\"mashable\" /> Fellow YouTuber and friend of Miller, Ethan Klein (also known under his alias of [[h3h3Productions]]) described Filthy Frank as the greatest YouTuber of all time in a 2017 interview with ''[[First We Feast]]''.<ref>''First We Feast'' (30 March 2017), [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Tgw2Kkmupg8 ''H3H3 Productions Does Couples Therapy While Eating Spicy Wings]'', retrieved 20 November 2018, event occurs at 1:39, via [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\n=== Pink Guy (2014\u20132017) ===\n{{redirect|Pink Guy|Michael Maxfield|Pink Man}}\nMiller has a passion for music composition. He has expressed that even before his YouTube career, he always had an interest in creating music and created his YouTube channel as a means of promoting his music. In an interview with ''[[Pigeons and Planes]]'', he said, \"I've always wanted to make normal music. I just started the YouTube channel to kind of bump my music. But then Filthy Frank and the Pink Guy stuff ended up getting way bigger than I thought so I had to kind of roll with it.\"<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" />\n\nMiller's music under Pink Guy is often comical, staying true to the nature of his YouTube channel. His debut album, ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'', debuted at number 70 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" /><ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|title=Billboard 200|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200|publisher=Billboard|access-date=18 January 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6TiHpwnx8?url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200?page=2|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Under his comedy rap stage name, Pink Guy, Miller has produced one mixtape, one album, and one extended play, ''Pink Guy'', ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'', and ''[[Pink Season: The Prophecy]]'', respectively. On 16 March 2017, Miller performed for the first time as Pink Guy at [[SXSW]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS41363|title=Pink Guy|work=SXSW 2017 Schedule|access-date=14 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014133223/http://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS41363|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Future plans were stated to include a \"long overdue\" tour, a third Pink Guy album and more progress on his personal music outside of the Pink Guy persona.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nHowever, as of 29 December 2017, Joji has ceased production of all Filthy Frank-related content, including Pink Guy music.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" /><ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\" />\n\n=== Joji (2015\u2013present) ===\nAside from the comedic and often rap-based music he created under the Pink Guy alias, Miller also created more serious and traditional music under another stage name, Joji, which became his primary focus in late 2017. Speaking on his transition from his YouTube career to his music career as Joji, Miller said to ''Billboard'' \"now I get to do stuff that I want to hear.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the article by ''Billboard'', he specified that 'Joji' isn't a character like Filthy Frank and Pink Guy. \"I guess that's the difference,\" he continues. \"Joji's just me.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time growing up in [[Higashinada-ku, Kobe]], Japan, Miller began to produce music and sing with friends as a side-hobby and a way to pass the time. After relocating to [[Manhattan]], New York, Miller expanded upon his music career by starting his Pink Guy persona, which paved the way for his Joji persona.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3habuLgROU|title=Joji's Journey from Viral Videos to Quality Music Music Life|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|date=1 November 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228064952/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3habuLgROU|archive-date=28 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller originally announced his Joji album on 3 May 2014 alongside the first Pink Guy album. However, Miller subtly cancelled the project until he began releasing music under the name PinkOmega.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=Trap Dumplings|date=4 June 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AMRP9JTHlw|publisher=George Miller|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115052248/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AMRP9JTHlw|archive-date=15 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller released two songs as PinkOmega: \"Dumplings\" on 4 June 2015<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=pinkomega \u2013 dumplings|date=4 June 2015|publisher=George Miller|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4mWh2NdVmDE|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001070159/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4mWh2NdVmDE|archive-date=1 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"wefllagn.ii 5\" on 28 August 2015,<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=pinkomega \u2013 wefllagn.ii 5|date=28 August 2015|publisher=George Miller|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwXmYzRVdfE|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118062345/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwXmYzRVdfE|archive-date=18 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> both of which were later released on the Pink Guy album ''Pink Season'', the latter being re-titled \"We Fall Again\".\n\nMiller intended to keep the music made under Joji a secret from his fanbase due to them mainly wanting his comedic music. In late 2015, two singles were released, titled \"Thom\" and \"You Suck Charlie\"; both were released under a false alias, but it was quickly leaked that the user behind the account was Miller,<ref>{{cite web|title=88 Rising \u2013 Rich Brian, Joji, & August 08 \u2013 Full Interview|publisher=Beats & Booze|date=20 August 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us-ebicLgd4|access-date=10 September 2018|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114175114/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us-ebicLgd4|archive-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which prompted him in January 2016 to publicly announce on [[Instagram]] that he was releasing a full-length commercial project titled ''Chloe Burbank: Volume 1''. In the same post, he linked his SoundCloud account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BAeMSDqtL99/|title=Joji \u2013 Chloe Burbank \u2013 Volume 1|last=Miller|first=George|date=13 January 2016|access-date=17 January 2017|via=Instagram}}{{dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Joji released several songs via the YouTube channel of Asian music label [[88rising]], the songs \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\", released on 26 April 2017, \"Rain on Me\", released on 19 July 2017,<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|title=Straight outta... China? The young Asian artists bucking hip-hop trends|last=Liu|first=Marian|publisher=CNN|access-date=9 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612210143/https://www.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"pigeons-and-planes-premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/04/joji-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time|title=Joji Returns With Stunning New Song \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\"|date=26 April 2017|access-date=26 April 2017|last=Skelton|first=Eric|publisher=Pigeons & Planes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815171207/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/04/joji-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/07/joji-rain-on-me|title=Listen to Joji's Gorgeous New Song \"Rain On Me\"|publisher=Pigeons & Planes|access-date=18 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818180327/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/07/joji-rain-on-me|archive-date=18 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"[[Will He]]\", released on 18 October 2017.<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes \u2013 Will He\" /> Joji was featured in the song \"Nomadic\" with the Chinese rap group [[Higher Brothers]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|publisher=88rising|title=Higher Brothers + joji \u2013 Nomadic (OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO)|date=12 July 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9l3_6yNjrs|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830235157/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9l3_6yNjrs|archive-date=30 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller performed live as Joji for the first time on 18 May 2017 in [[Los Angeles]]. The event was streamed by the [[Boiler Room (music project)|Boiler Room]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boilerroom.tv/session/88rising/|title=Boiler Room x 88rising|publisher=Boiler Room|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823205426/https://boilerroom.tv/session/88rising/|archive-date=23 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 October 2017, Miller released the debut single from his debut commercial project, ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]].''<ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite web|url=http://web2.empi.re/campaigns/?c=JojiInTongues|title=Pre-Save|website=Empire|access-date=18 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017203040/http://web2.empi.re/campaigns/?c=JojiInTongues|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The single, titled \"[[Will He]]\", was released on platforms [[Spotify]] and [[iTunes]].<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes \u2013 Will He\">{{Cite news|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/10/joji-will-he|title=Joji Shares Gorgeous New Single \"Will He\" [UPDATE]|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|access-date=18 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017211129/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/10/joji-will-he|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMiller's debut project under the moniker Joji, an [[Extended play|EP]] titled ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'', was released on 3 November 2017 by [[Empire Distribution]].<ref name=\"Empire\" /> A deluxe version of the EP was released on 14 February 2018 with 8 remixes of songs from the EP along with the release of \"Plastic Taste\" and \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\" as part of the track listing.<ref name=\"Deluxe EP\">{{cite news|last1=Desk|first1=BWW News|title=Joji Shares Video For 'Window' Announces Deluxe Version of 'In Tongues' EP|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-For-Window-Announces-Deluxe-Version-of-In-Tongues-EP-20180124|accessdate=26 January 2018|date=24 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126125704/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-For-Window-Announces-Deluxe-Version-of-In-Tongues-EP-20180124|archive-date=26 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Joji released the song \"Yeah Right\" in May 2018, becoming his first to chart on a ''Billboard'' chart, peaking at 23 on the ''Billboard'' R&B Songs chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/joji-yeah-right|title=Joji Drops New Song \"Yeah Right\"|work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=2018-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723004608/https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/joji-yeah-right|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMiller debuted ''[[Ballads 1]]'' under the label [[88rising]] on 26 October 2018, which quickly peaked the ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums Chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8483269/joji-ballads-debut-no-1-top-rb-hip-hop-albums-chart|title=Joji's 'Ballads 1' Debuts at No. 1 on Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130002239/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8483269/joji-ballads-debut-no-1-top-rb-hip-hop-albums-chart|archive-date=30 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after its release, Miller announced a North American tour, spanning 9 dates in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/joji-announces-ballads-1-north-american-tour-2019-134849|title=Joji announces 'BALLADS 1' North American tour 2019|website=AXS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094743/https://www.axs.com/joji-announces-ballads-1-north-american-tour-2019-134849|archive-date=22 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At that time, he was already on tour for ''Ballads 1'' in Europe.\n\nOn 4 June 2019, Miller announced his new single titled \"[[Sanctuary (Joji song)|Sanctuary]]\" through his Instagram page and released it on 14 June. It was accompanied by a music video, which was uploaded to [[88rising]]'s official YouTube channel.<ref name=\"SanctuaryAlbum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS_JqTJF4X/|title=SANCTUARY -- 6/14|date=June 4, 2019|via=instagram|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115191252/https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS_JqTJF4X/|archive-date=15 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJoji was featured in the song \"Where Does the Time Go?\" with Indonesian rapper [[Rich Brian]] on his second album ''[[The Sailor (Rich Brian album)|The Sailor]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Where Does the Time Go (feat. Joji) by Rich Brian|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-sailor/1469319614?i=1469319867|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January 2020, Miller announced another new single, \"[[Run (Joji song)|Run]]\", which released at midnight on 6 February 2020 alongside a music video released later that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sushitrash/status/1222976716642979842?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet|title=New single \u201cRun\u201d out February 6th 12:00AM ET worldwidepic.twitter.com/kFKlr1WxsL|last=JOJI|date=2020-01-30|website=@sushitrash|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Joji \u2013 Run (Official Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K09_5IsgGe8 |website=YouTube |publisher=88rising |accessdate=2020-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206223023/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K09_5IsgGe8&app=desktop |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 March 2020, he performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/joji-run-television-debut-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon-perfromance|title=Joji Makes TV Debut With Spotless Performance of \"Run\" on 'Jimmy Fallon'|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/03/02/first-look-joji-performs-on-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon/|title=Joji Performs On \"The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon\" (Watch Now)|date=2020-03-02|website=Headline Planet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, Joji announced another new single \"Gimme Love\" which released at midnight, and along with, announced his upcoming album, ''[[Nectar (Joji Album)|Nectar]]'', which is set to be released on 10 July 2020.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Musical style ====\nJoji's music has been described as [[trip hop]] and [[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\">{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2017/11/joji-interview-in-tongues|title=Joji's Journey from Viral Videos to Quality Music|author=Graham Corrigan|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|date=1 November 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102044118/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2017/11/joji-interview-in-tongues|archive-date=2 November 2017}}</ref> that blends elements of [[Trap music (EDM)|trap]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[Electronic music|electronic]], and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name=\"Crave\">{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/music/1340195-new-music-joji-miller-makes-name|title=New Music {{!}} Joji Miller Makes a Name for Himself|author=Patrick Green|date=3 November 2017|work=Crave|access-date=3 November 2017}}{{dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> His songs have been characterized as having \"down tempo, melancholic themes and soulful vocals\"<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\" /> with \"minimalistic production\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://earmilk.com/2017/04/28/listen-to-jojis-new-song-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time/|title=Listen to Joji's new song \"I don't wanna waste my time\"|author=Ruth Jiang|date=28 April 2017|publisher=Earmilk|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126032224/https://earmilk.com/2017/04/28/listen-to-jojis-new-song-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time/|archive-date=26 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe has been compared to electronic artist [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]],<ref name=\"Crave\" /> whom he also names as an influence alongside [[Radiohead]], [[Shlohmo]] and [[Donald Glover]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|publisher=MTV News|title=Joji Discusses His Rise From Parody Rap To Mainstream Music|date=6 November 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oPl5uUXzcxQ|access-date=14 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729083840/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oPl5uUXzcxQ|archive-date=29 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Pigeons and Planes]]'', Miller said that his music was inspired by his time growing up in Osaka and by boom bap instrumentals he listened to while attending [[Canadian Academy]].<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nMiller lives in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/joji-in-tongues-interview/|title=Joji Opens Up About YouTube Fame, Porn, & \"In Tongues\"|date=2018-09-17|work=Highsnobiety|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Miller often flies to Los Angeles for work and has a residence there.<ref>{{Citation|last=joji stuff|title=Joji Radio Interview \u2013 FlyFM|date=2018-09-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhI3qa5hLG0|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\nMiller has an undisclosed [[neurological disorder]] that causes stress-induced seizures. This is one of the reasons that led him to quit his YouTube career.<ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=The Viral Mastermind Behind The Harlem Shake Meme Wrote An Album About Heartbreak (HBO)|date=2017-11-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdaRIH_atZA|access-date=2018-09-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023233837/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdaRIH_atZA|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Joji discography}}\n\n=== As Pink Guy ===\n* ''Pink Guy'' (2014)\n* ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Pink Season: The Prophecy]]'' (2017)\n\n=== As Joji ===\n* ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Ballads 1]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Nectar (Joji album)|Nectar]]'' (2020)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{YouTube|user=TVFilthyFrank}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=4202274|title=The Filthy Frank Show}}\n\n{{Joji (musician)}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joji}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Comedy YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Japanese comedy musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Osaka]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Ukulele players]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese musician and web actor}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joji\n| birth_name         = George Kusunoki Miller<ref name=\"ACE Repertory\">{{cite web |title=ACE Repertory \u2013 Joji Kusunoki |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/writer/886198670/KUSUNOKI%20JOJI |website=www.ascap.com |accessdate=14 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330145422/https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/writer/886198670/KUSUNOKI%20JOJI |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| caption            = Joji performing in August 2018\n| image              = Joji Performing Live in 2018 (cropped).png\n| birth_date         = <!-- Do not change the birth date without adding a reliable source -->{{birth date and age|df=no|1992|9|18}}<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\">{{cite web|title=Joji on Apple Music|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/joji/1258279972|website=Apple Music|accessdate=14 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214143719/https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/joji/1258279972|archive-date=14 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Osaka]], Japan<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\" />\n| other_names        = {{flatlist|\n* Filthy Frank\n* Pink Guy\n}}\n| education          = [[Canadian Academy]]<br />[[New York Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* rapper\n* record producer\n}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| origin          = [[Higashinada-ku, Kobe]], Japan<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\" /><ref name=\"Canadian Academy\" />\n| genre           = {{ubl|'''Joji'''|{{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"billboard interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear' |last=Kelley |first=Caitlin |date=7 December 2017 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |archive-date=8 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[trip hop]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\" />\n* [[lo-fi]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\" />}}\n'''Filthy Frank''' / '''Pink Guy'''|{{hlist|[[Surreal comedy]]|[[satire]]|[[comedy hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank |title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career-Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear' |last=Kelley |first=Caitlin |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2018 |archivedate=8 June 2018 |url-status=live |quote=\"He won\u2019t rap on a Joji track like he does as Pink Guy&nbsp;...\" & \"Miller has been growing out of the brand of comedy associated with Pink Guy&nbsp;...\"}}</ref>}}\n\n}}\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vocals]]\n* [[ukulele]]\n}}\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[88rising]]\n* [[Doug Morris|12 Tone Music]]\n}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| channel_name = DizastaMusic\n| channel_name2 = TVFilthyFrank\n| channel_name3= TooDamnFilthy\n| years_active = 2008\u20132017\n| subscribers  = 13.1 million (combined)\n| views        = 2.4 billion (combined)\n| network      = ScaleLab<ref name=\"SocialBlade\">{{cite web|title=TVFilthyFrank YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|publisher=socialblade.com|accessdate=29 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816233823/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| silver_button   = yes\n| silver_year     = 2012\n| gold_button     = yes\n| gold_year       = 2015\n| diamond_button  = no\n| ruby_button     = no\n| stats_update    = 27 April 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''George Kusunoki Miller''' (born 18 September 1992<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\" />), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Joji''' and formerly by his online [[Pseudonym|aliases]] '''Filthy Frank''' and '''Pink Guy''', is a Japanese<!-- do NOT add half Japanese, half Australian; ethnicity does not belong in the lead section per [[MOS:BLPLEAD]] --> singer, songwriter, rapper, record producer, author, and former [[Internet celebrity|Internet personality]] and comedian.\n\nMiller's start as an entertainer began on his now defunct [[YouTuber|YouTube channels]], DizastaMusic, TooDamnFilthy, and TVFilthyFrank,<ref name=\"announcement tweet\">{{cite tweet|number=946807308541218816|user=FilthyFrank|title=This is old news but I figured I'd give an official statement. Thank you for your understanding and god bless.|date=29 December 2017|access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> that consisted of rap songs, rants, extreme challenges, [[ukulele]] performances<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsucurrent.nova.edu/soundbite-pink-season-by-pink-guy/|title=Soundbite: \"Pink Season\" by Pink Guy|work=The Current|access-date=14 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730112011/https://nsucurrent.nova.edu/soundbite-pink-season-by-pink-guy/|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and a [[shock humor]] show titled ''The Filthy Frank Show'', with most of the main characters played by Miller, including the titular character of Filthy Frank.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/01/pink-guy-pink-season-filthy-frank-george-miller-interview|title=The Man Behind Pink Guy's Bizarre Chart-Topping Album 'Pink Season'|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|access-date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308080936/https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/01/pink-guy-pink-season-filthy-frank-george-miller-interview|archive-date=8 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\">{{Cite news|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2017/12/joji-quits-pink-guy-filthy-frank-comedy|title=Joji Explains Decision to Quit Filthy Frank and Pink Guy as He Pursues Music Career|work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=29 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229223130/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2017/12/joji-quits-pink-guy-filthy-frank-comedy|archive-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> To complement his TVFilthyFrank channel, Miller produced [[comedy hip hop]] music under his Pink Guy alias, who is also a [[zentai]]-wearing recurring character on ''The Filthy Frank Show'', with his songs featured on the show and his discography spanning two full-length projects and an extended play. Miller's videos had widespread impact, including starting a viral dance craze known as the [[Harlem Shake (meme)|Harlem Shake]], which was directly responsible for the debut of [[Baauer]]'s \"[[Harlem Shake (song)|Harlem Shake]]\" song [[List of songs that debuted number one on the Billboard Hot 100|atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|title=Straight outta... China? The young Asian artists bucking hip-hop trends|first=Marian|last=Liu|work=CNN|access-date=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331104359/https://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|archive-date=31 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"mashable\">{{Cite news|url=https://mashable.com/2013/02/12/youtube-harlem-shake/#r8YJ3.GUFZqb|title=YouTube: Here's How 'Harlem Shake' Went Viral|last=Taylor|first=Chris|work=Mashable|access-date=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428154325/https://mashable.com/2013/02/12/youtube-harlem-shake/#r8YJ3.GUFZqb|archive-date=28 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Many YouTube personalities have made major or [[cameo appearance|cameo]] appearances on ''The Filthy Frank Show'', including [[h3h3Productions]], [[iDubbbz]], [[JonTron]], [[Michael Stevens (educator)|Michael Stevens]], and [[PewDiePie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wldE_4xjVQ|title=IT'S JUST A PRANK BRO|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=December 11, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225513/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wldE_4xjVQ|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Vuw-burI0|title=HUMAN CAKE|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=August 3, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225511/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Vuw-burI0|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6bQibFNs2E|title=A WAR IS COMING...|work=TVFilthyFrank|date=July 21, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113225514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6bQibFNs2E|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Miller stated he had retired the channel to focus on his music career, under the name Joji, producing more nuanced and serious music, releasing the EP ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'', which peaked at number 58 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and his debut studio album ''[[Ballads 1]]'', which reached number 1 on [[Billboard R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart|''Billboard''{{'}}s top R&B and hip-hop chart]] in November 2018. With this, Miller became the first Asian-born artist to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/joji-makes-history-on-billboard-chart/|title=Joji Becomes First Asian Artist to Top Billboard R&B/Hip-Hop Album Chart|work=Highsnobiety|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018|first=Renz|last=Ofiaza}}</ref> Miller's music has been described as a mix between [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[lo-fi]] and [[trip hop]].\n\n== Early life ==\nGeorge Kusunoki Miller<ref name=\"ACE Repertory\" /> was born on 18 September 1992,<ref name=\"Joji Apple Music\" /> in [[Osaka]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\">{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-for-New-Single-Will-He-Announces-New-EP-20171018|title=Joji Shares Video for New Single 'Will He'; Announces New EP|publisher=BroadwayWorld|date=18 October 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107012813/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-for-New-Single-Will-He-Announces-New-EP-20171018|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He attended an international school, [[Canadian Academy]], in [[Kobe]], Japan, where he graduated in 2012.<ref name=\"Canadian Academy\">{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/canadian.academy/docs/ca_review_fall_2012/7|title=CA Review Fall 2012|publisher=Canadian Academy|pages=4\u20135|access-date=16 January 2017|via=Issuu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927043055/https://issuu.com/canadian.academy/docs/ca_review_fall_2012/7|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At age 18, he left Japan and traveled to the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=VIz05lZMKyM|title=Joji Goes Desk Shopping, \"Phones\" Drake & Performs with 88rising|author=HYPEBEAST|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018|time=1:10|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> He was enrolled at New York Institute of Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyit.edu/files/special_events/Events_SOURCE_ProgramAbstracts_2016.pdf|title=Source: Symposium of University Research and Creative Expression|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2016|website=New York Institute of Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is half [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and half [[Australians|Australian]].<ref name=\"FrankExposed\">{{Citation|last=DizastaMusic|title=Filthy Frank Exposes Himself?|date=5 July 2017|url=https://archive.org/details/FILTHYFRANKEXPOSESHIMSELF_201707|access-date=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nMiller made attempts to maintain his privacy, such as deleting the video \"Filthy Frank Exposes Himself?\", where he revealed himself to be a college student in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and that he did not want to reveal personal information for fear of not being able to get a job later on due to the nature of his show.<ref name=\"FrankExposed\" />\n\n== Entertainment career ==\n=== ''The Filthy Frank Show'' (2011\u20132017) ===\nMiller created the Filthy Frank character during his time on his DizastaMusic [[YouTube]] channel, on which he created sketch comedy-based content. The channel started gaining popularity once he conceptualised Filthy Frank, a character who is described as the anti-vlogger of YouTube, in September 2015.<ref>{{Cite AV media|date=6 September 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6UYz2eNoS8&t=6m39s|title=TND Podcast #17 ft. George Miller a.k.a. Filthy Frank|time=6:39|publisher=The Needle Drop|access-date=22 January 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204014745/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6UYz2eNoS8&t=6m39s|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The first known video on this particular channel (before his creation of the Frank character) was uploaded on 19 June 2008, and was titled \"Lil Jon falls off a table\".<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=hB_LvjoAF2Q|title=Lil Jon falls off a table|date=19 June 2008|publisher=George Miller|access-date=30 June 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225124242/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hB_LvjoAF2Q|archive-date=25 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The DizastaMusic channel has over 915,000 subscribers and is nearing 170 million views {{As of|2019|9|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/DizastaMusic/about|title=DizastaMusic \u2013 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=30 June 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517212153/https://www.youtube.com/user/DizastaMusic/about|archive-date=17 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 August 2014, Miller uploaded a video to the DizastaMusic channel, announcing that he would not be posting any more video content onto the channel, under the risk of losing the channel due to the numerous copyright and community strikes it received.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=New Channel: TVFilthyFrank|date=15 August 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qSfcvIA366A|publisher=George Miller|access-date=26 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623131329/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qSfcvIA366A|archive-date=23 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn Miller's channel, TVFilthyFrank, he had many different series on his channel, such as \"Food\" (\u548c\u98df\u30e9\u30c3\u30d7), \"Japanese 101\", \"Wild Games\" and \"Loser Reads Hater Comments\". This channel currently has a total of 7.01 million subscribers and 1.02 billion views {{As of|2020|1|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/user/TVFilthyFrank/about|title=TVFilthyFrank \u2014 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=9 February 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808222325/https://m.youtube.com/user/TVFilthyFrank/about|archive-date=8 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|title=TVFilthyFrank YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics|publisher=Socialblade.com|access-date=9 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816233823/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tvfilthyfrank|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller opened a third channel, TooDamnFilthy, on 1 July 2014.<ref name=\"TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/about|title=TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About|publisher=George Miller|access-date=16 March 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406160233/https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/about|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On this channel he had two series, \"Japanese 101\", which is also featured on his main channel, and \"Cringe of the Week\", which is usually abbreviated to \"COTW\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TooDamnFilthy/playlists|title=TooDamnFilthy \u2013 Playlists|publisher=George Miller|access-date=13 October 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> {{As of|2019|9}}, TooDamnFilthy has 2.1 million subscribers and 258 million views.<ref name=\"TooDamnFilthy \u2013 About\" />\n\nOn 27 September 2017, Miller announced the release of his first and currently only book, titled ''Francis of the Filth'', which addresses things uncovered in ''The Filthy Frank Show'', and serves as a culmination of the series.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUrwgtQpjY8 |title=Francis Of The Filth (Out Now) |date=27 September 2017 |access-date=27 September 2017 |publisher=George Miller |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927230158/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUrwgtQpjY8 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2017, Miller released a statement on Twitter explaining that he had stopped producing comedy, including Filthy Frank, due to both \"serious health conditions\" and his personal lack of interest in continuing the series.<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|work=Billboard|access-date=29 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2018, Miller stated in a BBC Radio 1 interview that he had no choice but to stop producing comedy due to his health condition.<ref>{{Citation|last=Jambino|title=Joji Interview \u2013 BBC Radio 1 (Annie Mac)|date=2018-09-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BE34LTLrqoA|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Legacy ====\nMiller's Filthy Frank show has had a profound impact on internet culture, responsible for creating many [[internet memes]].<ref name=\"Diamondback\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dbknews.com/2016/12/02/filthy-frank-youtube-george-miller/|title=Filthy Frank and the inexplicable, weird, kind of gross side of Youtube|work=[[The Diamondback]]|date=December 1, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2018|first=Samuel|last=Atenza|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025613/http://www.dbknews.com/2016/12/02/filthy-frank-youtube-george-miller/|archive-date=8 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller's show has been hailed as \"the epitome of odd\".<ref name=\"Diamondback\" />\n\nMiller's videos had widespread impact, which included starting a viral dance craze known as the [[Harlem Shake (meme)|Harlem Shake]] back in 2013, which was directly responsible for the debut of [[Baauer]]'s \"[[Harlem Shake (song)|Harlem Shake]]\" song [[List of songs that debuted number one on the Billboard Hot 100|atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"cnn\" /><ref name=\"mashable\" /> Fellow YouTuber and friend of Miller, Ethan Klein (also known under his alias of [[h3h3Productions]]) described Filthy Frank as the greatest YouTuber of all time in a 2017 interview with ''[[First We Feast]]''.<ref>''First We Feast'' (30 March 2017), [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Tgw2Kkmupg8 ''H3H3 Productions Does Couples Therapy While Eating Spicy Wings]'', retrieved 20 November 2018, event occurs at 1:39, via [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\n=== Pink Guy (2014\u20132017) ===\n{{redirect|Pink Guy|Michael Maxfield|Pink Man}}\nMiller has a passion for music composition. He has expressed that even before his YouTube career, he always had an interest in creating music and created his YouTube channel as a means of promoting his music. In an interview with ''[[Pigeons and Planes]]'', he said, \"I've always wanted to make normal music. I just started the YouTube channel to kind of bump my music. But then Filthy Frank and the Pink Guy stuff ended up getting way bigger than I thought so I had to kind of roll with it.\"<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" />\n\nMiller's music under Pink Guy is often comical, staying true to the nature of his YouTube channel. His debut album, ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'', debuted at number 70 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" /><ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|title=Billboard 200|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200|publisher=Billboard|access-date=18 January 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6TiHpwnx8?url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200?page=2|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Under his comedy rap stage name, Pink Guy, Miller has produced one mixtape, one album, and one extended play, ''Pink Guy'', ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'', and ''[[Pink Season: The Prophecy]]'', respectively. On 16 March 2017, Miller performed for the first time as Pink Guy at [[SXSW]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS41363|title=Pink Guy|work=SXSW 2017 Schedule|access-date=14 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014133223/http://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS41363|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Future plans were stated to include a \"long overdue\" tour, a third Pink Guy album and more progress on his personal music outside of the Pink Guy persona.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nHowever, as of 29 December 2017, Joji has ceased production of all Filthy Frank-related content, including Pink Guy music.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes\" /><ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes\" />\n\n=== Joji (2015\u2013present) ===\nAside from the comedic and often rap-based music he created under the Pink Guy alias, Miller also created more serious and traditional music under another stage name, Joji, which became his primary focus in late 2017. Speaking on his transition from his YouTube career to his music career as Joji, Miller said to ''Billboard'' \"now I get to do stuff that I want to hear.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the article by ''Billboard'', he specified that 'Joji' isn't a character like Filthy Frank and Pink Guy. \"I guess that's the difference,\" he continues. \"Joji's just me.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|title=Singer/Producer Joji on His Career Flip From Crude Viral Comedy to Understated R&B: 'Now I Get to Do Stuff That I Want to Hear'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608065523/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8061822/joji-interview-will-he-filthy-frank|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time growing up in [[Higashinada-ku, Kobe]], Japan, Miller began to produce music and sing with friends as a side-hobby and a way to pass the time. After relocating to [[Manhattan]], New York, Miller expanded upon his music career by starting his Pink Guy persona, which paved the way for his Joji persona.<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3habuLgROU|title=Joji's Journey from Viral Videos to Quality Music Music Life|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|date=1 November 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228064952/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3habuLgROU|archive-date=28 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller originally announced his Joji album on 3 May 2014 alongside the first Pink Guy album. However, Miller subtly cancelled the project until he began releasing music under the name PinkOmega.<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=Trap Dumplings|date=4 June 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AMRP9JTHlw|publisher=George Miller|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115052248/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AMRP9JTHlw|archive-date=15 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller released two songs as PinkOmega: \"Dumplings\" on 4 June 2015<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=pinkomega \u2013 dumplings|date=4 June 2015|publisher=George Miller|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4mWh2NdVmDE|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001070159/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4mWh2NdVmDE|archive-date=1 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"wefllagn.ii 5\" on 28 August 2015,<ref>{{Cite AV media|title=pinkomega \u2013 wefllagn.ii 5|date=28 August 2015|publisher=George Miller|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwXmYzRVdfE|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118062345/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwXmYzRVdfE|archive-date=18 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> both of which were later released on the Pink Guy album ''Pink Season'', the latter being re-titled \"We Fall Again\".\n\nMiller intended to keep the music made under Joji a secret from his fanbase due to them mainly wanting his comedic music. In late 2015, two singles were released, titled \"Thom\" and \"You Suck Charlie\"; both were released under a false alias, but it was quickly leaked that the user behind the account was Miller,<ref>{{cite web|title=88 Rising \u2013 Rich Brian, Joji, & August 08 \u2013 Full Interview|publisher=Beats & Booze|date=20 August 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us-ebicLgd4|access-date=10 September 2018|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114175114/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us-ebicLgd4|archive-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which prompted him in January 2016 to publicly announce on [[Instagram]] that he was releasing a full-length commercial project titled ''Chloe Burbank: Volume 1''. In the same post, he linked his SoundCloud account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BAeMSDqtL99/|title=Joji \u2013 Chloe Burbank \u2013 Volume 1|last=Miller|first=George|date=13 January 2016|access-date=17 January 2017|via=Instagram}}{{dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Joji released several songs via the YouTube channel of Asian music label [[88rising]], the songs \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\", released on 26 April 2017, \"Rain on Me\", released on 19 July 2017,<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|title=Straight outta... China? The young Asian artists bucking hip-hop trends|last=Liu|first=Marian|publisher=CNN|access-date=9 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612210143/https://www.cnn.com/2017/08/02/asia/88-rising-asian-rap/index.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"pigeons-and-planes-premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/04/joji-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time|title=Joji Returns With Stunning New Song \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\"|date=26 April 2017|access-date=26 April 2017|last=Skelton|first=Eric|publisher=Pigeons & Planes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815171207/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/04/joji-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/07/joji-rain-on-me|title=Listen to Joji's Gorgeous New Song \"Rain On Me\"|publisher=Pigeons & Planes|access-date=18 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818180327/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/07/joji-rain-on-me|archive-date=18 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"[[Will He]]\", released on 18 October 2017.<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes \u2013 Will He\" /> Joji was featured in the song \"Nomadic\" with the Chinese rap group [[Higher Brothers]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|publisher=88rising|title=Higher Brothers + joji \u2013 Nomadic (OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO)|date=12 July 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9l3_6yNjrs|access-date=23 August 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830235157/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9l3_6yNjrs|archive-date=30 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Miller performed live as Joji for the first time on 18 May 2017 in [[Los Angeles]]. The event was streamed by the [[Boiler Room (music project)|Boiler Room]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boilerroom.tv/session/88rising/|title=Boiler Room x 88rising|publisher=Boiler Room|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823205426/https://boilerroom.tv/session/88rising/|archive-date=23 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 October 2017, Miller released the debut single from his debut commercial project, ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]].''<ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite web|url=http://web2.empi.re/campaigns/?c=JojiInTongues|title=Pre-Save|website=Empire|access-date=18 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017203040/http://web2.empi.re/campaigns/?c=JojiInTongues|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The single, titled \"[[Will He]]\", was released on platforms [[Spotify]] and [[iTunes]].<ref name=\"PigeonsandPlanes \u2013 Will He\">{{Cite news|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/10/joji-will-he|title=Joji Shares Gorgeous New Single \"Will He\" [UPDATE]|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|access-date=18 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017211129/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2017/10/joji-will-he|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMiller's debut project under the moniker Joji, an [[Extended play|EP]] titled ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'', was released on 3 November 2017 by [[Empire Distribution]].<ref name=\"Empire\" /> A deluxe version of the EP was released on 14 February 2018 with 8 remixes of songs from the EP along with the release of \"Plastic Taste\" and \"I Don't Wanna Waste My Time\" as part of the track listing.<ref name=\"Deluxe EP\">{{cite news|last1=Desk|first1=BWW News|title=Joji Shares Video For 'Window' Announces Deluxe Version of 'In Tongues' EP|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-For-Window-Announces-Deluxe-Version-of-In-Tongues-EP-20180124|accessdate=26 January 2018|date=24 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126125704/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Joji-Shares-Video-For-Window-Announces-Deluxe-Version-of-In-Tongues-EP-20180124|archive-date=26 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Joji released the song \"Yeah Right\" in May 2018, becoming his first to chart on a ''Billboard'' chart, peaking at 23 on the ''Billboard'' R&B Songs chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/joji-yeah-right|title=Joji Drops New Song \"Yeah Right\"|work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=2018-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723004608/https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/joji-yeah-right|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMiller debuted ''[[Ballads 1]]'' under the label [[88rising]] on 26 October 2018, which quickly peaked the ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums Chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8483269/joji-ballads-debut-no-1-top-rb-hip-hop-albums-chart|title=Joji's 'Ballads 1' Debuts at No. 1 on Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130002239/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8483269/joji-ballads-debut-no-1-top-rb-hip-hop-albums-chart|archive-date=30 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after its release, Miller announced a North American tour, spanning 9 dates in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/joji-announces-ballads-1-north-american-tour-2019-134849|title=Joji announces 'BALLADS 1' North American tour 2019|website=AXS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122094743/https://www.axs.com/joji-announces-ballads-1-north-american-tour-2019-134849|archive-date=22 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At that time, he was already on tour for ''Ballads 1'' in Europe.\n\nOn 4 June 2019, Miller announced his new single titled \"[[Sanctuary (Joji song)|Sanctuary]]\" through his Instagram page and released it on 14 June. It was accompanied by a music video, which was uploaded to [[88rising]]'s official YouTube channel.<ref name=\"SanctuaryAlbum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS_JqTJF4X/|title=SANCTUARY -- 6/14|date=June 4, 2019|via=instagram|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115191252/https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS_JqTJF4X/|archive-date=15 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJoji was featured in the song \"Where Does the Time Go?\" with Indonesian rapper [[Rich Brian]] on his second album ''[[The Sailor (Rich Brian album)|The Sailor]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Where Does the Time Go (feat. Joji) by Rich Brian|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-sailor/1469319614?i=1469319867|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January 2020, Miller announced another new single, \"[[Run (Joji song)|Run]]\", which released at midnight on 6 February 2020 alongside a music video released later that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sushitrash/status/1222976716642979842?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet|title=New single \u201cRun\u201d out February 6th 12:00AM ET worldwidepic.twitter.com/kFKlr1WxsL|last=JOJI|date=2020-01-30|website=@sushitrash|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Joji \u2013 Run (Official Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K09_5IsgGe8 |website=YouTube |publisher=88rising |accessdate=2020-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206223023/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K09_5IsgGe8&app=desktop |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 March 2020, he performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/joji-run-television-debut-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon-perfromance|title=Joji Makes TV Debut With Spotless Performance of \"Run\" on 'Jimmy Fallon'|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/03/02/first-look-joji-performs-on-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon/|title=Joji Performs On \"The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon\" (Watch Now)|date=2020-03-02|website=Headline Planet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, Joji announced another new single \"Gimme Love\" which released at midnight, and along with, announced his upcoming album, ''[[Nectar (Joji Album)|Nectar]]'', which is set to be released on 10 July 2020.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Musical style ====\nJoji's music has been described as [[trip hop]] and [[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 2\">{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2017/11/joji-interview-in-tongues|title=Joji's Journey from Viral Videos to Quality Music|author=Graham Corrigan|publisher=Pigeons and Planes|date=1 November 2017|access-date=3 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102044118/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2017/11/joji-interview-in-tongues|archive-date=2 November 2017}}</ref> that blends elements of [[Trap music (EDM)|trap]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[Electronic music|electronic]], and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name=\"Crave\">{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/music/1340195-new-music-joji-miller-makes-name|title=New Music {{!}} Joji Miller Makes a Name for Himself|author=Patrick Green|date=3 November 2017|work=Crave|access-date=3 November 2017}}{{dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> His songs have been characterized as having \"down tempo, melancholic themes and soulful vocals\"<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\" /> with \"minimalistic production\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://earmilk.com/2017/04/28/listen-to-jojis-new-song-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time/|title=Listen to Joji's new song \"I don't wanna waste my time\"|author=Ruth Jiang|date=28 April 2017|publisher=Earmilk|access-date=3 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126032224/https://earmilk.com/2017/04/28/listen-to-jojis-new-song-i-dont-wanna-waste-my-time/|archive-date=26 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe has been compared to electronic artist [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]],<ref name=\"Crave\" /> whom he also names as an influence alongside [[Radiohead]], [[Shlohmo]] and [[Donald Glover]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|publisher=MTV News|title=Joji Discusses His Rise From Parody Rap To Mainstream Music|date=6 November 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oPl5uUXzcxQ|access-date=14 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729083840/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oPl5uUXzcxQ|archive-date=29 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Pigeons and Planes]]'', Miller said that his music was inspired by his time growing up in Osaka and by boom bap instrumentals he listened to while attending [[Canadian Academy]].<ref name=\"Pigeons and Planes 3\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nMiller lives in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/joji-in-tongues-interview/|title=Joji Opens Up About YouTube Fame, Porn, & \"In Tongues\"|date=2018-09-17|work=Highsnobiety|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Miller often flies to Los Angeles for work and has a residence there.<ref>{{Citation|last=joji stuff|title=Joji Radio Interview \u2013 FlyFM|date=2018-09-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhI3qa5hLG0|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\nMiller has an undisclosed [[neurological disorder]] that causes stress-induced seizures. This is one of the reasons that led him to quit his YouTube career.<ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=The Viral Mastermind Behind The Harlem Shake Meme Wrote An Album About Heartbreak (HBO)|date=2017-11-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdaRIH_atZA|access-date=2018-09-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023233837/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdaRIH_atZA|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Joji discography}}\n\n=== As Pink Guy ===\n* ''Pink Guy'' (2014)\n* ''[[Pink Season (Pink Guy album)|Pink Season]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Pink Season: The Prophecy]]'' (2017)\n\n=== As Joji ===\n* ''[[In Tongues (EP)|In Tongues]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Ballads 1]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Nectar (Joji album)|Nectar]]'' (2020)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{YouTube|user=TVFilthyFrank}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=4202274|title=The Filthy Frank Show}}\n\n{{Joji (musician)}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joji}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Comedy YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Japanese comedy musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Osaka]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Ukulele players]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2008]\n", "name_user": "JJMC89", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joji_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Richard Schur", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Richard Schur\n| image = Richard_schur.jpg\n| caption = Richard Schur (2018)\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], [[Germany]]\n| nationality = German\n| field = [[Painting]], [[Abstract_art]]\n| training = [[Academy of Fine Arts, Munich]]\n| works = \n| patrons = \n| website = {{url|www.richard-schur.com }}\n}}\n'''Richard Schur''' (born 1971) is a German [[Abstract art|artist]].\n\n== Career ==\nRichard Schur studied at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich]] and graduated as [[Master of Fine Arts]] in 2000. From 2002 to 2008 he teached painting as [[Assistant professor]] with Jerry Zeniuk at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Munich]].<ref>Biography ''Richard Schur,'' http://www.artnet.com/artists/richard-schur/biography</ref> In 2005 he received the arts prize [[Bayerischer Kunstf\u00f6rderpreis]]. Schur's work has been shown in galleries and museums since 1998.<ref>Richard Schur CV ''Kristin Hjellegjerde'', London Retrieved 24 January 2020 https://kristinhjellegjerde.com/usr/library/documents/main/51/richard-schur_cv.pdf</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nSchur is known for complex abstract paintings, combining \"visual enquiry and art historical references with an element of playfulness\".<ref>MacDonald, Vici (2007) Richard Schur- Metaphorical Grids [http://www.artworldmagazine.com/contents_pgs/issue01.pdf ''Art World Magazine'', London, Issue 1, Oct/Nov 2007 p.9] </ref>  His works have been described as \"Metaphorical Grids\", containing clear color blocks, presented with the geometric precision of [[Piet Mondrian]].<ref>Larsen, Ingebj\u00f8rg Sofie (2015) ''Verve \u2013 Sebastian Helling vs Richard Schur,'' Norwegian Arts, Royal Norwegian Embassy, London. Archived from 13 February, 2015. Retrieved 24 January 2020 http://norwegianarts.org.uk/event/verve-sebastian-helling-vs-richard-schur/</ref>\n\nInitially Schur works with studies, allowing his motifs to evolve over an extended period of time, experimenting with color choices as part of an intuitive process. The motifs are then transferred to larger canvases or grounds, on which the artist uses the formal language of [[Hard-edge painting]] to \"gain a sense of clarity in the interaction of colors\". His art is also about bringing together the \"light, spirit and atmosphere\" of various locations around the world that have inspired him.<ref>Sebastian Helling & Richard Schur,  ''Wall Street International, Art''. Archived 2 February, 2015. https://wsimag.com/art/13103-sebastian-helling-and-richard-schur</ref>\n== Awards, Grants, Residendies ==\n* [[Bayerischer Kunstf\u00f6rderpreis]] of the Bavarian State Ministry of Science, Research and the Arts<ref> Richard Schur ''Bayerischer Kunstf\u00f6rderpreis 2005,''  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayerischer_Kunstf%C3%B6rderpreis#2005</ref>\n* ISCP, [[International Studio & Curatorial Program]], New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://iscp-nyc.org/resident/richard-schur |title=Richard Schur &#124; International Studio & Curatorial Program |publisher=Iscp-nyc.org |date= |accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n* Residency at the CCA, Centro Cultural Andraxt, Spain<ref>Artist Richard Schur, Artfacts. Retrieved 25 January 2020 https://artfacts.net/artist/richard-schur/14564 </ref>\n* Grant USA Scholarship of the Bavarian State Ministry of Sciences, Research and the Arts<ref>Artist Richard Schur Artfacts. Retrieved 25 January 2020 https://artfacts.net/artist/richard-schur/14564</ref>\n* Residency Cit\u00e9 Internationale des Arts, Paris<ref>[[Cit%C3%A9 internationale des arts]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Collections (Selection) ==\n* [[Pinakothek der Moderne]], Munich<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sammlung.pinakothek.de/de/artist/richard-schur |title=Sammlung &#124; Richard Schur |publisher=Sammlung.pinakothek.de |date= |accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n* CCA, Centro Cultural Andraxt, Spain<ref>{{cite web |url=https://artfacts.net/artist/richard-schur/14564|title=Richard Schur |last= |first= |date= 2014|website=artfacts.net|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n* CAAM, Centro Atl\u00e0ntico de Arte Moderno, Las Palmas de Gran Canaria, Spain<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caam.net/es/expos_int.php?n=151 |title=Cruce de colecciones |last= |first= |date= 2014|website=www.caam.net|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n* [[Guangdong Museum]] of Art, China<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdmoa.org/ |title=\u5e7f\u4e1c\u7f8e\u672f\u9986 |publisher=Gdmoa.org |date= |accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kristinhjellegjerde.com/usr/library/documents/main/51/richard-schur_cv.pdf |title=Resume |publisher=kristinhjellegjerde.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n'''2019'''\n* \u201eUntitled\u201c, Minus Space, Brooklyn, NY, USA<ref>http://www.minusspace.com/ Homepage Minus Space</ref>  \n* \u201eAlleando\u201c, Galerie Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany\n* \u201eThe Sound of Color, Galerie der Moderne\u201c, Stefan Vogdt, Munich, Germany<ref>https://www.galerie-vogdt.de/ Homepage Gallery Vodgt</ref> \n* \u201eJahresgaben\u201c, Kunstverein M\u00fcnchen, Munich, Germany \n\n'''2018''' \n* \u201eMetropolis\u201c, Galerie Ebbers, Kranenburg, Germany \n* \u201eSounds of Light\u201c, Galerie 21.06, Ravensburg, Germany\n* \u201eBetween Structure and Disorder\u201c, Kristin Hjellegjerde, Berlin, Germany \n* \u201eRoter Faden -Schwarz\u201c, Galerie Klaus Braun, Stuttgart, Germany \n* \u201e4ABSTRACTs2NOT\u201c, QuadrART Dornbirn, Austria \n\n'''2017'''  \n* \u201eThe Sound of Color, Galerie der Moderne\u201c, Stefan Vogdt, Munich, Germany \n* \u201eRichard Schur and Douglas Degges\u201c, Shim, Brooklyn, NY, USA  \n* \u201eRichard Schur en Stephan Fritsch\u201c, ACEC, Apeldoorn, Netherlands\n* \u201eArt New York\u201c, with Espace Meyer Zafra, New York \n* \u201eArt Market Hamptons\u201c, with Cross Mackenzie Gallery, Bridgehampton Museum, NY, USA  \n* \u201eGanz Konkret\u201c, Galerie Klaus Braun, Stuttgart, Germany \n* \u201eJahresgaben\u201c, Kunstverein M\u00fcnchen, Munich, Germany<ref>http://www.kunstverein-muenchen.de/ Homepage Kunstverein M\u00fcnchen</ref> \n* \u201eJahresgaben 2017\u201c, Kunstverein Augsburg, Germany \n* \u201eMittsommer - 30 Jahre Artothek!\u201c, Staedtische Artothek Munich Sammlung Opitz Hoffmann, Munich, Germany\n* \u201eMittsommer - 30 Jahre Artothek!\u201c, Stadtmuseum & Kunstsammlung Jena, Germany\n* \u201eMittsommer - 30 Jahre Artothek!\u201c, Galerie Klaus Braun, Stuttgart, Germany \n* \u201eMunich Impression\u201c, Galerie Claudia Weil, Friedberg-Rinnenthal, Germany \n\n'''2016''' \n*  \u201eMeadows\u201c, Cross Mackenzie Gallery, Washington DC, USA<ref>http://www.crossmackenzie.com/ Homepage Cross Mackenzie Gallery</ref>  \n*  \u201eManhattan Stories\u201c, Galerie Postel, Hamburg, Germany\n* \u201eBreak Ground: Amrhein-Welish, Schur-Seligson\u201c, ART 3, Brooklyn, NY, USA\n* \u201eWinter Spring Show 2016\u201c, Espace Meyer Zafra, Paris \n* \u201eLucky Draw\u201c, Sculpture Center, New York, USA  \n* \u201eWendezeiten\u201c, CCA Andraxt Kunsthalle, Mallorca, Spain \n* \u201eSammlung Opitz-Hoffmann\u201c, Stadtmuseum und Kunstsammlung Jena, Germany \n* \u201eSummer Saunter\u201c, Galerie Klaus Braun, Stuttgart, Germany \n* \u201eJahresgaben\u201c, Kunstverein M\u00fcnchen, Munich, Germany\n\n'''2015'''  \n* \u201eVerve\u201c, Kristin Hjellegjerde, London, United Kingdom<ref>https://kristinhjellegjerde.com/ Homepage Kristin Hjellegjerde Gallery</ref> \n* \u201eWeight for the Showing\u201c, Maddox Arts, London, United Kingdom \n* \u201eJahresgaben\u201c, Kunstverein M\u00fcnchen, Munich, Germany \n* \u201eSummer Show\u201c, Cross Mackenzie, Washington DC, USA \n* \u201eWe are pleased to invite you #5\u201c, Carlos Carvalho Arte Contemporanea, Lissabon, Portugal \n* \u201eNeue M\u00fcnchner Malerei VI\u201c, Galerie der Moderne, Stefan Vogdt, Munich, Germany \n* \u201eBushwick Open Studios\u201c, with ART 3, Brooklyn, N